<HEADLINE> Tanzanian, Rwandan Officials to Discuss Expulsion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Senior Tanzanian and
Rwandan government officials will meet on Sunday in Biharamulo
District, Region, to discuss the expulsion of 1,800
Rwandans by Tanzania early this year.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania people's Defense Forces Western Brigade
Commander, Brig. Gen. Ben Msuya, said the meeting will be
attended by senior officials from the Ministry of Home Affairs
and their counterparts in Rwanda, according to "The Guardian"
today.
</P>
<P>
Brig. Gen. Msuya declined to give details of the meeting but
sources in the neighboring Kigoma Region said the meeting will
focus on the expulsion early this year of 1,800 Rwandans who
settled in Kagera since 1959.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Rwandan government had been reluctant to
accommodate the expelled aliens claiming that some of them had
been sowing seeds of discord in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 1,800 expelled Rwandan aliens, some 188 were Hutus who
are disowned by the Rwandan government on reasons well known to
themselves," explained the sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the crackdown on the Rwandan aliens was
necessary because some of them were found to be ring leaders who
organized several armed robberies in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Our stand is that we were fed up with them because some of
them were armed bandits who terrorized residents in the region,
robbing them of money and property," the newspaper quoted the
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The bandits in recent years have hijacked passenger buses and
killed a lot of Tanzanians in the Kagera Region, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
