<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Unemployment Rate Slips to 4.6 Percent in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The nationwide job growth
across a wide range of businesses helped lower the US unemployment
rate to a new, 24-year low of 4.6 percent in November, the Labor
Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted rate of joblessness in November, a
further dip from 4.7 percent in October, was the lowest since
October 1973 when it also was 4.6 percent, the department said.
But the US lowest unemployment rate was recorded in March 1970,
when it was 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Employers added a seasonally adjusted 404,000 workers to their
payrolls, roughly a quarter of them in some retail establishments
such as department stores, gift shops, book stores and catalog
sales operations.
</P>
<P>
The jobs growth, even better than the robust 287,000 advance in
October, was the largest since February 1996 when workers were
streaming back to jobs temporarily interrupted by record snowfalls
in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
In retailing alone, the 105,000 increase was the most in nearly
three years.
</P>
<P>
However, the gains were not confined to retailing. Construction
employment rose 29,000 despite unseasonably cold weather.
Manufacturers increased 44,000 jobs, with the growth concentrated
at makers of electronic components, industrial machinery and
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Employment jumped 53,000 at temporary help firms, 15,000 in
engineering and management services, 13,000 in computer and data
processing services and 21,000 in health care.
</P>
<P>
Some economists have been concerned that labor shortages would
accelerate wage gains and stimulate inflation.
</P>
<P>
In November, average hourly earnings for non-supervisory
workers jumped 7 cents an hour to a seasonally adjusted 12.47
dollars, up 4.1 percent from a year ago. And the average workweek
grew by 0.3 hours to 34.8 hours.
</P>
<P>
November's unemployment rate for adult men fell to 3.8 percent,
from 4.1 percent in October. The rate held steady at 4 percent for
adult women. Among whites, the rate fell from 4.1 percent to 3.8
percent. Among blacks, it rose from 9.5 percent to 9.6 percent and
among Hispanics it fell to 6.9 percent from 8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
