<HEADLINE> No Going Back on Land Acquisition: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 5 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe today
told over 5,000 delegates to the ruling party's third national
conference in Mutare of east Zimbabwe that there is no going back
on land acquisition plan for resettlement purposes.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who is expected to get the full support of the
delegates to proceed with acquisition, hit back at critics of the
program.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe government's plan to acquire about 1,500 farms
for resettlement purposes has raised local and international
outcry.
</P>
<P>
''Let the message be clear. There is no going back. It is
utter nonsense to argue that our people rely on the (white)
commercial farmers for their food and other products,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, ''land is the people's sovereign asset. It is
their home, economic resource, a social and cultural asset, their
religious shrine, their heritage and very livelihood.''
</P>
<P>
''How does it arise that a mere 4,000 (white) farmers control
more than half of the arable land. Is it sustainable
agriculture?'' he said, reminding the delegates that land
disparities caused by colonialism triggered the liberation war.
</P>
<P>
He added since Britain had renounced responsibility of funding
the acquisition exercise as agreed during the 1979 Lancaster
House conference, Zimbabwe would not beg for assistance.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Mugabe has tasked the ruling ZANU (PF) national
conference to ratify the decision of the central committee to
re-admit party members who were expelled for standing as
independents in local government and parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
However, the former rebels were required to confess and
publicly admit their wrong by contesting elections as
independents.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who criticized the weakness of the party's propaganda
machinery, appealed to the leadership to be involved in the data
registration exercise to ensure that the party was well organized
at lower levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
