<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Pak President on Constitutional Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Former president Farooq
Leghari said here today the recent constitutional crisis that led
to his resignation reflected "a conflict" between his "perceptions
of national interest" and those of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Leghari, who resigned Tuesday after refusing to sign a
reference against Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah as required by the
Sharif government, said this in response to a letter from Sharif
Thursday in which he had offered to forget the past bitterness.
</P>
<P>
"The divergence in our perception of the issue at the center of
the recent crisis and the consequent bitterness that plagued out
relationship has no longer any relevance," Sharif said in his
letter to Leghari.
</P>
<P>
Leghari in his response wrote: "you are right in saying that
there was a divergence in our perceptions of the issue at the
center of the recent crisis."
</P>
<P>
He said he never harbored any bitterness against anyone during
these trying times.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, I tried my best to mediate the recent conflict in the
supreme interest of the law and institution," Leghari said, adding
"my consideration of the national interest is clearly different
from yours."
</P>
<P>
The former president pointed out that the recent events that
led to his resignation "reflected a conflict between our
fundamentally dissimilar perceptions and attitudes towards the law
and constitution, the concept of their supremacy, and the need and
importance of strengthening institutions of state rather than
pandering to the interest of the person."
</P>
<P>
"Both before and after my resignation, and thereafter, my views
remain the same," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
