<HEADLINE> SAARC to Celebrate Charter Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) will celebrate its 12th Charter
Day on December 8, said a press release issued today by the
Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC was established on December 8, 1985 with the signing
of its Charter by the heads of state or government from
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment, the SAARC has taken a number of
significant steps to expand the areas of cooperation including
socio-economic and poverty eradication which are utmost relevant
to the member countries, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Other issues high on the SAARC agenda include matters relating
to children, women and disadvantaged groups of society, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
The most significant achievement of the SAARC in recent years
is the operationalization of the SAARC Preferential Trading
Arrangement (SAPTA) in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Another important target has been set to achieve South Asian
Free Trade Area (SAFTA) by 2001, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
In order to further vitalize and enhance the effectiveness of
the organization in achieving its objectives, the ninth SAARC
summit held in May in Male, the Maldives has decided to establish
a Group of Eminent Persons to develop a long-range vision and
formulate a perspective plan of action including a SAARC agenda
for 2000 and beyond which will spell out targets that can and must
be achieved by 2020, the press release said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
