<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Tables Precondition for EU Enlargement Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said here today that the European Union (EU) would start
detailed membership talks only with those applicants that are
ready to join the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The EU enlargement talks are expected to start early next year
when Britain takes over the six-month rotating EU presidency in
January 1998.
</P>
<P>
Cook was quoted by the BBC Television as saying today that
Britain supported the ambitions of all 10 Eastern European
countries that have applied to join the EU.
</P>
<P>
"We support the ambitions of all of them. That's why during the
British presidency we will be calling them all to London for a
conference to exchange political dialogue and to work out how we
can best support all of them coming into the European Union," Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Cook said that not all of them were ready now.
"Detailed negotiations can really only be held with those who are
ready for membership," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
On the European Parliament's suggestion for the EU to start
accession talks with all applicants, Cook said that it would not
do "any favors for those countries that are not ready for
membership, not ready to withstand the competitive pressures and
challenge of membership of the single market."
</P>
<P>
"It would be a much more sensible process, helping those
countries to get ready for membership rather than plunging them in
before they are ready," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the EU executive Commission's proposal, the EU will limit
its first wave membership talks with Poland, the Czech Republic,
Hungary, Slovenia, Estonia and Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
