<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders Up in October for 5th Consecutive Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The US factory orders rose
in October for the fifth consecutive month as a result of
increased demand for aircraft, autos, paper and food products, the
Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the commerce report, orders increased 0.3 percent
to a seasonally adjusted 337.2 billion US dollars following a 0.4
percent rise a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods, expensive items intended to last at
least three years, edged 0.1 percent lower, better than some
advance estimate of a 0.3 percent drop last week.
</P>
<P>
But strength in transportation equipment and instruments and
measuring devices wasn't enough to offset declines in primary
metals such as steel and metal products, industrial machinery and
electrical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Orders for non-durable goods rose 0.8 percent, the same as the
previous month. Food and paper products showed the largest
increases.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, shipments of factory goods, a measure of current
production, slipped 0.1 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders rose 0.4 percent, the fifth
increase in six months. The increase in the backlog can indicate
that factories are too busy to keep up with their orders, an
inflation warning flag. Manufacturing inventories, up 15 of the
last 16 months, increased 0.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
