<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Vice-president Slams Disloyal MPs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Vice-president Simon
Muzenda today criticized legislators who publicly oppose bills in
parliament without consulting the party caucus and threatened to
have them discarded from the party.
</P>
<P>
"They may be intelligent, brave and rich but if they are
disloyal to the party they are of little value," he said in his
address to the ruling ZANU (PF) party's third annual conference.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians last week refused to pass the Finance No. 2
Bill to allow the government to impose on the controversial war
veterans levy of five percent of income tax of all workers with
effect from January next year.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda also said factionalism and indiscipline, which had
created independents within the party remained the biggest threat
to its supremacy over the country's weak opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
He noted that efforts by the leadership to end factionalism
were proving difficult.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda, who last year severely criticized members for
indiscipline, appealed for loyalty to the party constitution and
principles.
</P>
<P>
"Loyalty should start from the bottom and permeate all
structures. It is necessary to look at ourselves critically. Our
survival depends on our ability to organize ourselves, otherwise
we will be overtaken by other parties," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
