<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Economy Hit by Peace Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The setback in the Mideast peace
process widely blamed on Israel's hard line policy has taken its
toll of the Palestinian economy, the Middle East News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Economic Unity Council being convened at the Arab
League this week said the real GNP in Palestinian self-rule areas
retreated by 2.9 percent in 1996 to 1.3 billion U.S. dollars
compared with 1995 when the economy posted a minus 4.9 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
The losses were caused by Israel's repeated and prolonged
closures of the self-rule areas for security reasons, the Council
noted.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued by the Council, per capita share
of the GNP in Palestinian areas dropped by 6.7 percent in 1996
compared with 1995. The years 1993 and 1994 witnessed a record low
of 12 percent on average in per capita share of the GNP, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1993 signing of the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration
of Principles, per capita share of the GNP rolled back by 21.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Also, the report said that Palestinian foreign trade shrank by
10 percent in 1996, with export commodity value slashed from 2.23
billion U.S. dollars in 1995 to 1.811 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade constitutes 75 percent of Palestinian GNP.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank report released last week said that in 1996 the
Palestinian economy sustained losses far exceeding the total
international aid the Palestinians have received since the peace
process started.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, in 1996 there were 180 "closure" days
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, with a daily loss of 8-10 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since the Oslo accord, Palestinian economy has been drained of
3 billion U.S. dollars, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
