<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Extends Authorization for US Exercises in Haiti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has given the Pentagon an open-ended mandate to continue U.S.
military training in Haiti, which was to expire by the end of this
month, a Pentagon spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
In extending the authorization earlier this week, Clinton set
no specific limit on time or troop numbers, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Joining the training dubbed as "New Horizon," the U.S. troops,
have been doing a variety of engineering work, construction,
medical training and other activities in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
The number of U.S. troops there varies but typically totals 400
to 500, including about 100 support forces who provide logistical
and administrative help for the exercises.
</P>
<P>
A three-year U.N. peacekeeping mission in Haiti, performed by
Canadian and Pakistani troops, ended on November 30, leaving
U.N.-trained Haitian police in charge of the nation's security.
</P>
<P>
Clinton sent 20,000 U.S. troops to Haiti in 1994 to force out a
military regime and restore President Jean-Bertrand Aristide.
</P>
</TEXT>
