<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britons' Life Expectancy Variations Widening: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The gap in life expectancy of
the British people is widening sharply between the north and the
south, the poor and the rich, according to a latest study.
</P>
<P>
Citing a study in the Journal of Epidemiology &AMP; Community
Health, local press reports today said that although people in all
parts of Britain are living longer, those in the north and in
affluent areas are extending their life expectancy much more
rapidly than those in the south and in the inner cities.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that from 1984 to 1986, the difference between
the highest and lowest life expectancy areas was 5.2 years for men
and 4.3 years for women.
</P>
<P>
However, by 1992 to 1994 the gap had stretched to 6.7 years for
men and 4.7 for women.
</P>
<P>
The gap between life expectancies of the rich and the poor has
also widened. In the mid-1980s life expectancy in the most
affluent areas exceeded that in the most deprived by 2.8 years for
men and 1.6 years for women. Ten years later, the gap had
increased to four years and 2.4 years respectively.
</P>
<P>
The study, by the National Institute of Epidemiology at Surrey
University, suggested that more suicides, murders and accidental
deaths, among male residents of deprived areas are to blame,
together with higher rates of heart disease and lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
It also indicated that health education messages are not
getting through to the poorest, with poor diet and heavy smoking
and drinking causing above-average levels of lung cancer and heart
disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
