<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Signs Convention Against Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus is among the countries
that signed the convention against landmines, demonstrating its
sincere efforts to reduce tension and promote mutual confidence
on the island, Cyprus News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
After signing the document Thursday in Canada, Cyprus' Foreign
Ministry's Permanent Secretary Alecos Shambos said that the
Cypriot government decided to sign the convention as "it is fully
aware of the urgent need to remove all these weapons of death and
destruction from the island."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot official pointed out that the government decision
was taken despite the fact that Turkey continues to violate
international law and maintains over 35,000 troops on the island.
</P>
<P>
"My government sincerely hopes that the Convention on
Anti-Personnel Landmines will have a positive effect on our
efforts to stop more innocent lives from being lost so
senselessly," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. reports, there are 39 minefields and
booby-trapped areas inside the U.N.-controlled buffer zone
dividing the island, set up in 1964 when conflict between the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities broke out.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that well over 16,000 landmines have been laid
in these areas since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and took
over the northern third of the island in the wake of a failed
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Shambos stressed that "our signing must therefore be seen as a
gesture of goodwill on our part and as a unilateral contribution
to the objective of complete and eventual demilitarization of the
Republic of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
The demilitarization proposal, put forward by Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides in 1993, provides for the disband of the
republic's National Guard and handover of its arms to the
U.N. peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the proposal provides for the simultaneous
withdrawal of the Turkish occupation troops from the island and
the disband of the Turkish Cypriot armed forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Farmers Step Up Action on Beef Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- With an emergency aid package
for the beef industry under consideration after protests by
farmers against cheap beef imports, the British government warned
them they were not above law.
</P>
<P>
Thursday night, farmers from across the South-East marched on
Dover and blocked the entrance to the port, preventing all
vehicles from leaving or entering.
</P>
<P>
Scuffles broke out after police reopened the port to allow
ferries to leave, and four protesters were arrested.
</P>
<P>
The National Farmers' Union (NFU) blamed the government for the
blockade against Irish and Continental beef imports.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement with its Irish counterpart, the NFU said
the action was caused by the government's refusal to claims
compensation for farmers.
</P>
<P>
Sue Scott, the NFU spokesman, said, "Farmers have simply had
enough over the last 18 months. Negotiation has not worked and
they are frustrated and fed up."
</P>
<P>
There are reports that farmers also blockaded Seaforth in
Liverpool, Stranraer and Cairnryan in south-west Scotland, and
Holyhead and Fishguard in Wales.
</P>
<P>
Jack Cunningham, minister of agriculture, said the protesters
were short-sighted if they could not see the damage they were
doing to Britain's reputation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook also warned farmers they were not
above the law in their protests against beef imports and said that
he understood the concerns but the government had to take a firm
line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
