<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Sets Conditions for Executing Oil-For-Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said today that it will
not implement the third phase of the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal
until the distribution plan for this period is approved by the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
It also conditioned implementation upon the execution of all
the contracts that it has signed with other countries in the
previous two phases of the deal.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, a spokesman of Iraq's Foreign Ministry
blamed Thursday's resolution of the U.N. Security Council for only
considering the export of oil by Iraq, but neglecting the delivery
of food and medicine to the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made just after the end of the second phase of
the oil-for-food deal which was started a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is under strict economic sanctions, which bars export of
oil, Iraq's main revenue earner, imposed by the U.N. in 1990 after
its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In April, 1995, the U.N. Security Council adopted resolution
986 to allow Iraq to sell 2 billion dollars worth of oil every six
months to buy food and medicine for its people.
</P>
<P>
The latest U.N. Security Council resolution opened the third
phase of the oil-for-food deal signed between Iraq and the U.N.
according to resolution 986.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that Iraq fully exported the amount
of oil in the first and second phases of the deal, but the food
and medicine contracts signed in the two phases have not been
totally implemented.
</P>
<P>
He added that in the second phase of the program, only a few
contracts have been approved, and the humanitarian goods arriving
in Iraq is far from enough to meet the needs.
</P>
<P>
He accused the United States and Britain of obstructing the
approval of the contracts.
</P>
<P>
All oil-for-food contracts must be approved unanimously at the
U.N. Sanctions Committee which includes the U.S. and Britain as
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
