<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Calls on French People to Face History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today called on the French people to face history and again
recognized the responsibility of the French state during the Vichy
collaboration period for the deportation of thousands of Jews.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, France of the occupation (period) existed. Yes, the
arrests, the round-ups, the deportations were organized with the
assistance of the French administration," said Chirac during a
ceremony to place "Jewish files" of the Vichy period at the
Memorial of Unknown Jewish Martyrs in Paris.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for Chirac since he became president in
May 1995 to publicly recognize the responsibility of France for
the death of thousands of Jews during World War II.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, the camps of internment and transit, such as Pithiviers,
Beaune-la-Rolande, Drancy, Compiegene and many others, were under
the responsibility of that (French administration of the Vichy
period), even the census and establishment of the files (on
Jews)," he said.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Le Monde said that Chirac made the statement
when some politicians of France's center-right oppositions are
closing in with the extreme-right National Front before the
regional elections to be held in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that France should recognize the responsibility of
its past, not for "self-whipping with the past," but for
"inventing the present on the healthy and clear basis."
</P>
<P>
President of the Gaullist Rally for the Republic Philippe
Seguin said recently that France was "self-whipping" by putting on
trial former Vichy official Maurice Papon, accused of crimes
against humanity for deporting 1,690 Jews from 1942 to 1944.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
