<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttle Columbia Returns to Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The American space shuttle
Columbia returned to its home port in Florida this morning after a
16-day space science mission, ending the eighth and final flight
of the year.
</P>
<P>
Columbia and its six crew members swooped through a clear,
chilly sky and landed safely on the runway at the Kennedy Space
Center. Mission control officials greeted the the astronauts and
congratulated their successful journey which covered some 104
million-kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Among the achievements of the mission, two spacewalking
astronauts saved the runaway 10 million U.S. dollar Spartan
science satellite by catching it with their hands.
</P>
<P>
The two astronauts, NASA's Winston Scott and Japan's Takao Doi,
tested a new crane being developed for space station assembly and
to evaluate construction techniques in their second spacewalking.
</P>
<P>
Other crew members grew crystals, studied flames and cultivated
plants in orbit.
</P>
<P>
Although disappointed with Spartan, which failed to conduct
solar watching, NASA managers were pleased with the results of the
microgravity research and grateful for an extra, unplanned
practice spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
Astronauts Winston Scott and Takao Doi spent most of their
first spacewalk trying to snare the slowly tumbling Spartan after
it was sent spinning away from the shuttle by an inadvertent nudge
of the shuttle's robot arm.
</P>
<P>
In the second spacewalking, the two astronauts set up a small
hand-operated crane and practiced moving a simulated space station
component.
</P>
<P>
The spacewalks were NASA's last planned tests in orbit before
construction of the new station begins next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
