<HEADLINE> 160 Million People Suffer from Diabetes Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- President of the Ethiopian
Diabetic Association Zeleke Wedajo said today that about 160
million people all over the world are suffering from diabetes,
one of the major killer diseases next to AIDS and cancer.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Zeleke when he was speaking at a
meeting here to observe the 1997 World Diabetes Day which falls
on today.
</P>
<P>
Zeleke said that over the past few years the incidence of
diabetes around the globe has been increasing at an alarming
rate.
</P>
<P>
He said, the International Diabetes Federation which was
organized in 1950 has now a membership of 126 states, adding that
medical care and treatment for diabetes are included in the
national health programs of 62 nations.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Ethiopian government to integrate diabetes
treatment and care in the national health program.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Yirdaw Damtaw, public relations
officer of the Ministry of Health of Ethiopia, said that although
diabetes is a life-long disease with no cure, it is possible to
curb its progress through effective treatment and proper personal
care.
</P>
<P>
"The worst side of diabetes is that most of the victims do not
know that they have the disease," he said and called upon health
professionals and pertinent governmental bodies to raise the
public's awareness about diabetes.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Diabetic Association was set up 14 years ago
with a major objective of helping diabetics in every respect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
