<HEADLINE> Blair Urges Farmers to Halt Beef Blockades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair today urged British farmers to stop blockading ports in
protest at imports of cheap beef from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he sympathized with the farmers but they must stop
blockading ports. He insisted law and order must be upheld and
harbors and lorry routes kept open.
</P>
<P>
"We understand very well the distress and difficulty of British
beef farmers at the present time," Blair said at a ceremony
marking Britain's six-month stint as president of the European
Union starting in January.
</P>
<P>
"The rule of law must be upheld and we will ensure that it is,"
he said. "The scenes at some of the ports and harbors don't help
the farmers' case."
</P>
<P>
He also said taxpayers would pay 1.4 billion pounds (2.3
billion US dollars) in support of the beef industry -- a signal
that the government is not considering compensation for farmers.
</P>
<P>
Welsh farmers began blockading ports Monday in an attempt to
stop imports of cheaper Irish beef, and they have since been
joined by their Scottish and English colleagues. The farmers have
forced a number of trucks with Irish beef to turn back.
</P>
<P>
Thursday night, some 250 farmers demonstrated at the
southeastern English port of Dover and three people were arrested
in scuffles with police as protesters tried unsuccessfully to stop
trucks leaving the docks.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations continued today despite government
assurances that officials were considering help for farmers.
Farmers say the government's latest ban on beef sold on the bone
is another blow to the beef industry when British consumer
confidence was beginning to recover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
