<HEADLINE> AL Chief Starts Visits to UAE, Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdul-Meguid left here today on visits to United
Arab Emirates (UAE) and Iran, which will highlight Islamic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid is expected to take part in the opening of an
Afro-Arab fair in Sharjah, UAE, in which a number of Arab and
African businessmen will take part with the aim of campaigning for
investment in Arab and African countries.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving here, The AL chief said that he will participate
in the summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC)
in Iranian capital Tehran as an observer.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid, whose visit to Tehran will be the first of its
kind, voiced his hope that his meetings with Iranian officials
will lead to further development of the Arab-Iranian ties.
</P>
<P>
The league's chief said that he plans to have intensive talks
with Iranian officials on all major issues concerning the Arab
nation, including the territorial dispute between UAE and Iran,
especially as Abu Dhabi has expressed its readiness to resort to
the International Court of Justice to resolve their dispute.
</P>
<P>
Iran and UAE have been in a territorial dispute over the
sovereignty of three Gulf islands of Abu Musa and the greater and
lesser Tonbs.
</P>
<P>
He also described Egypt's participation in the OIC summit as "a
vital matter." Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa left for
Tehran today heading a delegation to ministerial meetings
preceding the summit.
</P>
<P>
He added that such a big Islamic gathering in Tehran attended
by heads of state or prime ministers of 54 OIC member nations will
have its own significance.
</P>
<P>
High on the agenda of the 8th Islamic summit running on
December 9-11 are the status of Jerusalem and other occupied Arab
territories as well as the structural readjustment of the OIC.
</P>
<P>
The summit will also discuss conditions in Afghanistan and
Somalia, the territorial dispute between the United Arab Emirates
and Iran over the sovereignty of three islands and other issues in
Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
The Jeddah-based OIC, established in 1970 with a view to
rallying the ranks of the Islamic world, holds a summit meeting
every three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
