<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Calls EU Tobacco Advertising Ban "Incomprehensible" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The German government has called a
European Union ban on tobacco advertising "incomprehensible" and
threatened to take legal actions against it.
</P>
<P>
German government spokesman Peter Hausmann said today in Bonn
that the decision made by EU health ministers late Thursday to
phase out tobacco advertising and sports sponsorship by the year
2006 was "incomprehensible" to German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and
his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated an early warning by German Health Minister
Horst Seehofer that Germany could launch a lawsuit to the European
Court of Justice if the EU decision was approved by the European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The ban also angered German tobacco and publishing industries
which said that it contravened the principles of freedom of
expression enshrined in the German constitution and would lead to
massive job losses.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates of the Central Association of German
Advertising Industry, the EU ban would cost Germany some 500
million marks (280 million U.S. dollars) in lost advertising
revenues annually.
</P>
<P>
The German Ufa cinema advertising company also predicted that
about a fourth of German cinemas would go bankrupt due to the ban.
</P>
<P>
However, a number of German health organizations, including the
Association of Doctors, welcomed the EU decision, describing it as
"a step in the right direction." They also called for further
measures to protect non-smokers.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Austria were the only EU states voting against the
tabacco advertising ban Thursday. Spain and Denmark abstained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former S. African President Served with Third </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) today served a third subpoena on
former state president PW Botha, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
The subpoena, which was accepted by a security guard at
Botha's home, required Botha to testify on December 19 before
TRC, a special court authorized by the government led by the
African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
The second subpoena served on Botha was legally announced
defective because it neglected to tell him an exact time of
testifying. Botha was originally required to testify at Friday's
public inquiry into the activities of the former National Party
government's state security council (SSC).
</P>
<P>
Botha's lawyer, Ernst Penzhorn, would not say whether his
client would ignore the third subpoena.
</P>
<P>
Botha has already refused to appear publicly before the TRC,
calling it a "circus".
</P>
<P>
The TRC first subpoenaed him in October to appear at the first
round of its inquiry into the SSC. However, the subpoena was
waived on the grounds of ill-health after Botha produced a
medical certificate.
</P>
<P>
Botha said today he had not made himself guilty of any serious
violations of human rights and was thus not prepared to apologize
for or ask for amnesty for any such deed.
</P>
<P>
In a long-awaited written submission of more than 1,700 pages,
Botha questioned the TRC's legitimacy and asked why he had been
subpoenaed to appear before it while Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP)
leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi, who had rejected the commission
outright, had not.
</P>
<P>
The IFP is the biggest black opposition party in South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
