<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Takes Measures to Stabilize Grain Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Grain Trade
Enterprise said that it has enough stock to stabilize the rise in
grain price, that may result from damage to this year's harvest
due to the untimely rain.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency today, the enterprise
which is responsible for grain trade in the east African country,
has pumped more than 10,000 tons of teff, the Ethiopian staple,
into markets in Addis Ababa, Mekele, Gonder, Nazret and several
other towns to control the rising price of teff witnessed over
recent months.
</P>
<P>
Feleke Wakjira, head of the Sale Department of the enterprise,
told local pressmen that a quintal of teff is sold at an average
price of 200 Birr (about 29 US Dollars) at the stated cities and
towns, while wheat goes for an average 150 Birr (about 22 US
Dollars), adding that the measures taken by the enterprise have
enabled to reduce grain price hike by about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said, the Ethiopian Grain Trade Enterprise has the
financial capacity for the purchase and storing of up to 1
million tons of grain.
</P>
<P>
The enterprise has finalized preparations to commence purchase
at 17 branches and 64 stations throughout the country to back up
existing stock, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier announcement from the Disaster
Prevention and Preparedness Commission of Ethiopia, over 4.2
million people need relief food of 572,831 tons in 1998 due to
poor grain harvest this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
