<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Revised Services Offer Wins Broad WTO Welcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- China's comprehensive revised
services offer was warmly welcomed by members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) as the Working Party on China's accession had
its sixth meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
"Members judged it to be an important document, one on the
basis of which they could build the future bilateral services
negotiations," said Pierre-Louis Girard, chairman of the Working
Party on China.
</P>
<P>
China's revised offer has been circulated among members since
November 20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side has spent five months, starting from last May,
revising the service schedule and has conducted concentrated
negotiations with some member countries on services, Long Yongtu,
China's vice minister of foreign trade and chief trade
representative, told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We have given notice that during the morning session of this
meeting, many delegations gave a positive assessment to the
tremendous efforts of the Chinese side, and raised many requests
and proposals, to which we are very grateful," Long said.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that our service offer has provided a basis
for future negotiations which will be conducive to the
comprehensive progress of market access negotiations and will
contribute to the final conclusion of the negotiations," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, as Girard said in his summing-up, members also
expressed concerns about "remaining horizontal and sector-specific
restrictions, many of these being core restrictions limiting the
geographic or quantitative service commitments."
</P>
<P>
"Members further noted that the offer was not as comprehensive
as they would have wished," Girard said. Certain service sectors
like the basic telecommunications sector were missing.
</P>
<P>
Responding to all those concerns, Long said that the Chinese
side is willing to "further clarify and explain the content of the
schedule through bilateral consultations."
</P>
<P>
No decision has yet been taken on a date for the next meeting of
the Working Party on China, but the multilateral process in Geneva
is expected to resume early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
