<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams Food-for-Oil Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Only 10 percent of the
humanitarian supplies under the U.N. oil-for-food deal has been
distributed, an Iraqi minister was today quoted by Egypt's Middle
East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with the news agency, Minister of Trade of
Iraq Mohamed Mehdi Saleh was complaining of the slow distribution
of food and medicine to the Iraqi people during the first two
phases of the deal.
</P>
<P>
He cited reports of the U.N. Children's Fund to confirm that
27.5 percent of Iraq's children under five are suffering from
malnutrition and that 1.2 million Iraqis have died due to the
U.N. sanctions imposed in 1990, which bars Iraq from exporting
oil, the main revenue earner.
</P>
<P>
To ease the hardship of the Iraqi people, the U.N. Security
Council adopted resolution 986 in April, 1995 to allow it to sell
2 billion dollars worth of oil every six months.
</P>
<P>
The ensuing oil-for-deal has been carried out for two phases
since a year ago. The Security Council Thursday approved to open
the third phase of the deal.
</P>
<P>
But a third of Iraq's revenues of oil sales goes to the U.N.
Special Commission monitoring Iraq's weapons system and to the
indemnities for the victims of the 1991 Gulf War, Saleh said.
</P>
<P>
The lack of foreign currency to buy food and medicine has led
to millions of deaths, he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
