<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and
French President Jacques Chirac held an informal meeting this
afternoon in Bonn in preparation for next week's European Union
enlargement summit in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
But both sides declined to disclose the outcome after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France have apparent differences on a series of EU
issues. While Paris has been insisting that the EU should first
conduct institutional reforms prior to taking in any new eastern
European members, Germany wants to promote the EU enlargement in
parallel to its internal reforms.
</P>
<P>
At the Luxembourg summit on December 12-13, the 15 EU members
will try to formulate a common strategy to push forward the
enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France also differ on the issue of who will head
the future European central bank.
</P>
<P>
Germany and most other EU countries expect the Dutch head of
the European Monetary Union, Wim Duisenburg, to take the post, but
France wants the governor of the Bank of France, Jean-Claude
Trichet to assume the job. 
