<HEADLINE> S. African Business People Cautiously Optimistic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The South African
business community today expressed cautious optimism over the
prospects of the country's economic growth in 1998, the South
African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"There is no room for complacency. We view the year ahead with
cautious optimism, anticipating that the 1997 trend of
consolidation will continue into the first half of 1998, with
faster growth thereafter," said Raymond Parsons, director general
of the South African Chamber of Business (SACOB).
</P>
<P>
Presenting an economic outlook for the next 12 months, he said
his organization forecast a GDP growth of 2.3 percent next year
against the 1.8 percent likely to be achieved this year.
</P>
<P>
The government had forecasted a GDP growth of two percent this
fiscal year and three percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Inflation, at 8.2 percent in 1997, is expected to continue its
downward trend to about seven percent in 1998, Parsons predicted.
</P>
<P>
He said a strong growth in manufacturing, construction and
electricity sectors would partly offset expected lower
agricultural and mining output.
</P>
<P>
"A great deal of this optimism will obviously depend on the
government's fiscal discipline and the credible implementation of
the GEAR (growth, employment and redistribution) macro-economic
strategy which remains the pillar of the current economic
performance," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa's economic performance in the new year
was also going to hinge on the world sentiments toward gold
which, although it contributes only six percent to South Africa's
GDP, employed more than 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
It also hinges on the extent of the East Asian financial
crisis and how other countries survive its effects.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the El Nino phenomenon was bound to hit economic
performance as much as the low gold prices and the low export
demand.
</P>
<P>
Crime, bank rate cuts are other factors, Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern that the recent legislation of the Labor
Relations Act and the Basic Conditions of Employment Bill would
effect flexibility in the labor market and stifle growth,
especially small and medium scale enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Employment is expected to fall by two percent in 1997 and 1.5
percent in 1998," said Parsons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
