<HEADLINE> Two Rhinos Airlifted from S. Africa to Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Two black rhinos were
airlifted today from their home in South Africa to Seronera,
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The mother rhino and her calf, which got off a military plane
this afternoon, were received by the Ngorongoro District
Commissioner, Emos Mphuru, on behalf of the government of
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of the two rhinos is part of continental efforts
of Africa to conserve the endangered species, which has
diminished from 10,000 in number in 1960s to 2,400 today due to
merciless poaching.
</P>
<P>
Rhino horns have been used in making handicrafts, while other
parts of the animal have been used as ingredients in medicine.
</P>
<P>
Wildlife experts have said that there are less than 15 rhinos
in the Ngorongoro crater.
</P>
<P>
The calf, two and a half years old, has been named Thandi
Lushuge Rankoi, in honor of South African ambassador to Tanzania
who played very important role in bringing the two rhinos.
</P>
<P>
The veterinarian who accompanied the rhinos, Moris Kileo, of
the Tanzania National Park, said the mother rhino, called Ms
Phanton, is nine tons in weight and pregnant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
