<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hawkish Minister: West Bank Security Zones Vital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEITWELL (West Bank), December 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Minister
of National Infrastructure Ariel Sharon said here today that it is
vital for Israel to set up security zones in the West Bank in
order to protect Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when explaining his plan of setting up
security zones in the West Bank to a group of foreign reporters he
organized today on a special tour of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
It is vital for Israel to set up security zones in the West
Bank, particularly the one parallel to the Jordan River Valley and
the other, east of the 1949 Armistice Line, said Sharon.
</P>
<P>
Sharon is a key member of the cabinet, known for his tough
stand toward the Mideast peace accords, and one of the four-member
ministerial committee responsible for formulating the policies of
Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 3,000, Beitwell is a Jewish village set up
on the top of a hill in 1981. The village is located just east to
the 1967 Green Line, not far from the Ben Gurion Airport in the
west.
</P>
<P>
Indicating the hills around the village, Sharon said most of
the areas along the Green Line are barren hills, but they have the
main water resources for Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Israel must put these areas under its control and so I
suggested on December 2 to the cabinet ministerial committee to
set up a security zone of 7 to 10 kilometers wide east of
Armistice Line overlooking the coastal plain," he said.
</P>
<P>
Showing his strategic map of the West Bank, Sharon said that
from the security point of view, Israel should have the
20-kilometer-wide Jordan River Valley security zone, separating
Jordan and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) territories.
</P>
<P>
Within the West Bank, Sharon also mapped out several other
security zones surrounding the main cities under the management
of the PNA, as well as the Jewish settlements in the West
Bank. All these security zones will be linked with "strategic
roads" as he called them.
</P>
<P>
Most of these security zones inside the West Bank are
populated Palestinian areas and their security must be maintained
in the future by the Israeli Defense Forces (IDF), he said.
</P>
<P>
On the way to the Jordan River Valley, Jewish settlements can
be seen in many places and the constructions of "strategic roads"
are going on.
</P>
<P>
Sharon said these "strategic roads" are crucial for the IDF to
maintain security and will be beneficial to both the PNA and
Israel. Hospitals and schools will be built along these
"strategic roads" and the Palestinians can also use them in the
future, he said.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the PNA of not doing enough in fighting terrorism,
which he said is the main reason hindering the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a cabinet member, he is opposed to the
formation of a Palestinian state, but it is impossible to ignore
the fact that the PNA has already been accepted by many countries
in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that the "safe passage" will be built between Gaza and
the West Bank and it will be in the nature of "corridor."
</P>
<P>
Sharon's security zones cover about 50 percent of the West
Bank territories and he could not give a definite answer whether
the PNA will accept it or not.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his doubt about the Oslo Accords, saying some
amendments could be made to it if possible.
</P>
<P>
On the second-stage Israeli troop redeployment in the West
Bank, he said Israel will hand over some territories to the PNA,
mainly from the "Zone B," which are the 450 villages under the
PNA administrations but the securities are under the Israeli
control.
</P>
<P>
He said it will take some time for the committee to finish its
job on redeployment, but the government is firm on the security
issues in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Probe False Spy Data Affair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Knesset
(parliament) will start to investigate next week the affair of
"false information" about Syrian attack on Israel, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A Knesset subcommittee monitoring secret services is expected
to inquire an anonymous Mossad agent who has been proved to supply
bogus information, according to the radio.
</P>
<P>
In summer last year, the Israeli intelligence service received
reports from the agent, who has long been considered dependable,
that Syria has intended to launch a lightning strike on the Golan
Heights, Syrian territory occupied by Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
The agent said the Syrians have planned to recover part of the
Golan Heights and will use it as leverage in negotiations with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The information reportedly made the Israeli government misjudge
Syria's policy toward Israel and raised tensions in the region.
</P>
<P>
Nissim Zvilli, a member of the subcommittee, has called for an
examination of possible political motives behind the affair.
</P>
<P>
He has suspected whether politicians, who have been wishing to
see the deterioration of the Israeli-Syrian relations, are behind
the affair.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Foreign Minister David Levy have
downplayed the effect of the misinformation on the government
decision regarding Syria.
</P>
<P>
They have said the decisions of such an important issue are
made according to many factors, not just one piece of information
or another. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HSBC On Impacts Of Lower Oil Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- OPEC's decision to increase its
oil production ceiling effectively opened the floor under the oil
price prompting a drop from 19 U.S. dollars per barrel to 18
dollars per barrel, HSBC Holdings plc expected.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the output ceiling may seem irrelevant given
the fact that current output already exceeds the level.
</P>
<P>
However, for those countries which have spare capacity, such as
Saudi and the UAE, the increased quota will mean extra production,
said market experts in HSBC.
</P>
<P>
It was believed the decision will boost total OPEC oil
production from 27.9 million barrels per day currently to around
28.4 million b/d.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, prospects for growth in oil demand are not
particularly encouraging. There is a good chance that the oil
price could fall as low as 16 dollars per barrel by the first
quarter next year, they expected.
</P>
<P>
It was also estimated that a sustained fall to 16 dollars per
barrel in 1998 would shave 0.1 per cent off world inflation,
perhaps 0.2 per cent if the pass-through from costs to consumer
prices was particularly fast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Protect Interests of Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Ismet Sezgin said here today that Turkey will continue to
safeguard the rights and freedom of the Turkish Cypriots, Turkish
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with a visiting Turkish Cypriot delegation, Sezgin
said that Turkey's policy towards Cyprus will remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
He said that Ankara will continue its efforts to maintain
peace and stability in Cyprus though unstable factors are
increasing day by day.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriots-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island following a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin, also the defense minister, added that the Cypriot
government has no right to apply for the European Union
membership on behalf of the whole island.
</P>
<P>
Dervis Eroglu, a senior Turkish Cypriot official and head of
the visiting delegation, said that Turkish Cypriots will not give
up its struggle for equal status.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots believe that Turkey will, as always,
extend its full support to its brother on the divided island, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 the
establishment of "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is
only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and the international community have been
striving to reunite the two communities, but so far no
substantial results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Cyprus worsened recently after Greece and Turkey
held frequent military exercises on the island and in the Aegean
Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
