<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, December 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- A Russian military cargo plane crashed today eight
minutes after take-off from Irkutsk's airport in Siberia. At
least 46 people on board the aircraft were killed and an estimated
150 died at the crash site on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Among the 46 people on board, 16 were crew members; the rest
were passengers, reported the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which crashed at 09:44 Moscow time (06:44 GMT),
ploughed into a four-story residential building in a satellite
town of the city of Irkutsk some 5,000 kilometers east of Moscow,
said the news agency.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The foreign ministers' meeting of the Organization of
Islamic Conference (OIC) opened here today to prepare agenda and
documents for the eighth OIC summit to be opened Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural session, Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi said that the Islamic World must pave the way and
prepare the necessary grounds for it "to play a historical role in
founding the future international order and participate in its
management within the framework and on the basis of democratic
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
The eighth OIC summit is to be held at a critical and
sensitive historical and international juncture at the threshold
of the third millennium, he said, tumultuous developments are
unfolding in the world and the Islamic world is also undergoing
fundamental transformations.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least nine people were killed and 69 others
injured in three powerful bomb explosions that ripped through the
compartments of three trains in India's Tamil Nadu and Kerala
states today, Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that three or five people were killed in
two blast incidents.
</P>
<P>
Police said that they suspected the hand of a religious
fundamentalist organization in the act.
</P>
<P>
Today is the fifth anniversary of the demolition of the
disputed mosque in Ayodhya of Uttar Pradesh in northern India by
the Hindu people. More than 1,000 people were killed in the
nation-wide violence following the demolition act five years ago.
</P>
