<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Investors Looking To Other Regions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shenzhen in
Guangdong Province has been increasing business with other inland
provinces and regions.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the city, the earliest special
economic zone in China, has more than 1,500 interprovincial
projects, with at least 15 billion yuan (1.8 billion U.S. dollars)
in investment, which is being referred to as the "Shenzhen
Investment Phenomenon".
</P>
<P>
A recent visit by a group of Shenzhen entrepreneurs to
Chongqing, China's newest municipality, resulted in contracts
worth two billion yuan (240 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen's deputy-Mayor Guo Rongjun, who was head of a business
delegation, said that Shenzhen's investment in other parts of the
country, which used to be targeted at short-term profits in
coastal provinces, has shifted to the central and western part of
China in response to state-policy emphasis on these areas.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen's investment mainly takes the form of share-holding
and deals with city infrastructure in response to local needs, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
