<HEADLINE> Folk Art Booming In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Folk arts and other traditional
art forms have become sizeable and prosperous after going through
a period of rehabilitation and expansion in the Chinese capital
over recent years.
</P>
<P>
A major folk art exhibition of superb arts and crafts works,
which opened in Beijing Friday, appeases to the eyes of visitors
with displaying objects of at least 20 different traditional art
forms like kite-making, paper-cutting, mask-painting, pottery, egg
shell painting, clay figurines, and silk figurine.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a number of modern art forms like iron-painting,
pebble-painting, knitted hangings, walnut handicrafts, fish-bone
art, and glass, have also been on display.
</P>
<P>
To develop the traditional folk arts, Beijing municipality set
up a folk artists' association in the early 1980s, which now has
at least 400 local artist members.
</P>
<P>
The association has had a series of cultural exchange programs
with foreign artists, and hosted folk art exhibitions or lectures
in many countries like Japan, Singapore, and Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
