<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Refugees Eager to Return Home from India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Tribal refugees of Bangladesh's
Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) staying at Shilachhari in the Indian
state of Tripura have expressed their strong desire to return to
their homeland after the peace agreement on CHT issue signed on
December 2, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The tribals are in a festive mood and still rejoicing the
signing of the peace accord by preparing special dishes for their
family members and friends in all six refugee camps in Tripura.
</P>
<P>
Tribal Refugee Welfare Association (TRWA) leaders opined that
the treaty between the Bangladesh government and the tribal
organization had fulfilled the long-cherished dream of the hill
people.
</P>
<P>
A total of 526 refugees of 143 families returned home Saturday
from Thakumbari refugee camps through Tabalchhari frontier of the
district, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, 13,024 tribal refugees of 2,547 families have
returned home from different refugee camps in the Indian state of
Tripura during the 15-day period.
</P>
<P>
The ceaseless repatriation in the fourth and fifth phases
covering a period of 15 days from November 21 ended Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The sixth phase of repatriation is likely to start shortly to
bring back the rest of some 44,359 tribal refugees staying in six
refugee camps in Tripura excluding a sizable number of registered
refugees, as revealed from the discussion held between the leaders
of the TRWA and the deputy commissioner Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
