<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh Makes Continuous Efforts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Alleviating Poverty
</P>
<P>
By Hao Fusheng
</P>
<P>
DHAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- As one of the poorest countries
in the world, Bangladesh has made continuous efforts in past
decades in alleviating its poverty and gained some achievements in
this regard. But the task of poverty-alleviation in the country is
still very arduous.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's population reached 124.3 million at the end of
1996-97 fiscal year ending June 30 and the total area of the
country is only 147,570 square kilometers. The population density
is 842 per-kilometer. The heavy population pressure is one of the
reasons for the poverty.
</P>
<P>
The country's GDP in 1996-97 fiscal year was 32.979 billion
U.S. dollars with a growth rate of 5.7 percent while the per
capita GNP was only 276 dollars. This shows that the economic base
is weak.
</P>
<P>
The poverty in the country is characterized by landlessness,
low investment, low income and low saving rate.
</P>
<P>
Over half the people in the country are living below the
poverty line, with over 80 percent of them live in the rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
In the past 26 years since the independence in 1971, the
burden of poverty has been pressuring this South Asian country
hardly to gasp for breath.
</P>
<P>
All previous governments of the country had attached
importance to the poverty alleviation work and made some
achievements in population control, calamity-combating,
infrastructural construction and foodgrain production, owing to
their continuous efforts.
</P>
<P>
But, however, observers here say that the achievements are
limited due to the weak economic base, bad natural calamities,
mismanagement and gradual reduction of foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi governments have undertaken many projects such as
food production, income generation, employment, education as well
as infrastructural construction in a bid to alleviate poverty.
</P>
<P>
However, these projects have not been successfully implemented
because of mismanagement, bureaucracy, lack of infrastructural
facilities and specially lack of a strong united leadership.
</P>
<P>
The speed of poverty alleviation is therefore very low. Based
on income measurement, the proportion of people living in poverty
fell from 57.5 percent in 1987 to 51.7 percent in 1994. This
represents roughly only one percent decline in poverty per year
during the period. If this trend continues, it will take over 50
years to eliminate the poverty in the rural areas, according to
Dr.Hossain Zillur Rahman of Bangladesh Institute of Development
Studies.
</P>
<P>
Both the previous and the present governments have claimed to
be committed to building Bangladesh into a country without poverty
and hunger. But neither of ruling and opposition parties stop
making constant harassment against each other, the political
situation in the country has always been in the state of
instability in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Some donor countries, international financial agencies and
foreign investors constantly warned both parties that if they do
not solve the disputes between them peacefully and continue to
confront with each other, they would reduce aid or to invest in
other places. The reduction of the foreign aids and investment
hinders the country from alleviating poverty at a faster space.
</P>
<P>
According to some experts from research institutes at home and
abroad, international donors group and Non-Governmental
Organization (NGOs), Bangladesh is a developing country with a
fine potential. It has fertile land, rich human and natural
resources, particularly rich gas and oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
The poverty, though it is a hard core to crash, can be
gradually reduced and finally eliminated so long as the Bangladesh
government takes a correct policy suitable for the actual
conditions of the country, both ruling and opposition parties take
the whole situation into account and try to create a favorable
environment for poverty alleviation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Children's Village Being Built in Eastern Fujian Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Construction work of China's
seventh SOS Children's Village, a kind of orphanage, has started
in Putian City in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
SOS Children's Villages International, a non-government
charitable organization, will fund the construction and provide
200,000 US dollars for expenses every year.
</P>
<P>
The village plans to adopt orphans from Fujian and the
neighboring provinces. The children live in groups referred to as
"families", which have unmarried or divorced women acting as
"mothers" to look after them and help them develop special skills
like singing and painting.
</P>
<P>
The first Chinese SOS Children's Village was opened in the
north China port city of Tianjin in 1986, and it was followed by
the cities of Yantai, Qiqihar, Nanchang, Chengdu and Kaifeng.
</P>
<P>
The international organization's first village was opened by an
Austrian doctor in 1949, and it now has at least 300 children's
villages in about 100 countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
