<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gathering More Evidence Of Earliest Human Ancestors in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Stone tools discovered recently
in southwestern China seem to provide evidence to back up the
belief of some paleontologists that the ancestor of modern man
appeared in China some two million years ago, about a million
years earlier than what people have long believed.
</P>
<P>
Various sizes of crudely-chipped stone tools were discovered
over the last two months by a team of Chinese paleontologists.
Prof. Huang Wanbo, the team's leader, told Xinhua in his Beijing
office that, "The existence of early humans at that time can be
confirmed because, obviously, the stone chipping was done by hand."
</P>
<P>
This was the second time for Prof. Huang and his co-workers to
find evidence of the existence of the two-million-year-old Wushan
Man, a descendent of 'homo erectus', or men who stood erect, near
the southern bank of the Yangtze River in the Three Gorges area.
</P>
<P>
Huang regards the two finds as "a major challenge" to
traditional theories of human origin and evolution, which excluded
the possibility of a human ancestor in Asia prior any older than
one million years.
</P>
<P>
"Although we didn't find human fossils this time, there are
abundant fossils at the site, and I believe we'll find more
evidence in future," said Huang, who is with the Chinese Academy
of Sciences' Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and
Paleoanthropology.
</P>
<P>
The site, named Longgupo, is located in Wushan County
administered by Chongqing Municipality, in southwestern
China. Many mammal fossils, stone tools, part of a jaw and a
single tooth of what they initially classed as H. erectus were
discovered during the first excavation work from 1985 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
However, there was some controversy about Wushan Man's
existence, which was questioned by some of Huang's colleagues at
that time because of a lack of convincing materials like human
fossils and stone artifacts.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of traces of Wushan Man may mark the beginning of
a massive hunt for fossils of much earlier ancestors, people who
lived two million to four million years ago, in the southwestern
part of China, the paleontologist says.
</P>
<P>
The State Science and Technology Commission is planning to fund
just such a program in future, Huang says, and notes that he and
his colleagues will establish a vertebrate paleontology and
paleoanthropology research center at Longgupo next year as part of
the same effort.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Trade Union Threatens to Intensify Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Trade Union has
threatened that it will resume and intensify the general strike
Sunday if no agreement can be reached tonight with the Finance
Ministry, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Trade Union has asked its members to
obey the back-to-work orders issued by the National Labor Court
until Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
At the Ben Gurion Airport in Tel Aviv, workers have returned to
work today and allowed 13 flights of foreign airlines to land.
</P>
<P>
The Trade Union and the Finance Ministry are expected to
resume negotiations this afternoon, which were broken off
Thursday night on the instructions of Attorney-General Elyakim
Rubinstein, who said there would be no talks with workers who
were in contempt of court order.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which was launched Wednesday in protest against
government plans for wages reform and privatization, has
paralyzed the country by effectively shutting down airports,
seaports, banks, the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange, government offices
and state-owned industries.
</P>
<P>
The strike was triggered by the remarks made by Finance
Minister Ya'acov Neeman Monday, who called the striking workers
"exploding bombs" and enemies from within.
</P>
<P>
In response to the assault, Trade Union Chairman Amir Peretz
declared the strike Tuesday night at an emergency gathering of
thousands of union members in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The strike is the latest round in the Trade Union's battle
against government economic reform plans, which have sparked
fears that worker's rights would be harmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
