<HEADLINE> President: New Initiatives on Cyprus Expected Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has said that new initiatives aimed at solving the
Cyprus problem are expected early next year, Cyprus News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering of Cypriots living in London Friday
night, Clerides said various initiatives with the aim to resolve
the Cyprus issue are expected to be launched around March
immediately after the February presidential elections in the
government-controlled southern part of the island.
</P>
<P>
The president said one initiative will be launched by
U.S. Presidential Emissary for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke and
another by British Special Representative for Cyprus, Sir David
Hannay.
</P>
<P>
Clerides added that an initiative of the European Union will
also be launched.
</P>
<P>
"All these initiatives are within the framework of the
U.N. Secretary-General's good offices mission," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island as a bizonal, bicommunal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of direct talks between the two communities'
leaders were held under the U.N. auspices in July and August
this year, but no agreement was reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
