<HEADLINE> Burundi President Wants to Change Venue for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Burundi President Pierre
Buyoya said he wants the Arusha talks on Burundi to be shifted to
other African countries, a local report said today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Uganda paper the New Vision, Buyoya
claimed that Tanzania has been biased and does not recognize the
Burundi government and has given its embassy in Dar es Salaam to
the rebels for fighting his government.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi president was quoted as saying that he wants a
neutral venue like Kampala, Harare or Addis Ababa. He also wants
former Tanzanian President Juilius Nyerere to be joined by a team
of other mediators.
</P>
<P>
But Buyoya's internal opponents, former presidents Sylvestre
Ntibatunganya, Jean Baptiste Bagaza, and Parliament Speaker
Leonce Ngendakumana said Tanzania is still credible and Nyerere
should continue to be mediator, according to the local report.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here from Dar es Salaam said a consultative
meeting of all Burundi parties on the conflict would be held in
the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha, but no date has been fixed
for the talks.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a Ugandan delegation ended a four-day
visit to Burundi on Friday after meeting Buyoya, who took power
in an army coup in July 1996, and opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
Mike Mukula, a member of the delegation, said the visit by six
parliamentarians was a private initiative, and that a report
would be later presented to Nyerere and Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni. 
</P>
