<HEADLINE> US Official's Visit Focuses on War in N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The guerrilla war in northern
Uganda will be one of the topics during the visit by U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the New Vision paper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions concerning the visit Friday, Susan Rice,
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs, said
Albright ''is very concerned about the Lord's Resistance Army
(LRA) and reports of new atrocities against civilians by the
rebels in the north.''
</P>
<P>
LRA is a rebel group of Christian fundamentalists operating in
the north and has some bases in southern Sudan. In its 11 years
of guerrilla war to topple the government led by President Yoweri
Museveni, hundreds of civilians have been killed.
</P>
<P>
But the effective strength of the LRA is in its dramatic
decreasing, from more than 2,000 fighters in previous years, to
about 700-800 soldiers including children fighters now this year.
</P>
<P>
Albright will visit Ethiopia, Rwanda, the Democratic Republic
of Congo and Zimbabwe, besides Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The US State Secretary will meet President Museveni for talks
also on the political and military situation in the Great Lakes
region, the paper said. 
</P>
