<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Brings Rain, Winds to Southern California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES December 5 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rain and strong winds
swept across Southern California today. Weather officials said
the storm would continue until next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists have warned the public of El Nino's impending
influence for months. The phenomenon's occurrence succeeded by
diverting the storm toward California and the southwestern states.
</P>
<P>
In the Los Angeles area, heavy rain arrived just before noon
and winds across the region gusted up to 50 miles (80 kilometers)
per hour.
</P>
<P>
Five-day forecasts through next Tuesday called for up to 4
inches of rain in Southern California, nearly 2 inches in Arizona,
2.75 inches in Colorado and up to 1.5 inches over Southern Utah.
</P>
<P>
In advance of the storm, teams from the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers worked to clear the Los Angeles River flood control
channel and swift-water rescue teams drilled in Southern
California. Homeowners in the flood-prone areas filled sandbags
supplied by emergency agencies.
</P>
<P>
Despite heavy rain and high winds earlier in the day and late
into the evening, no deaths or damages were reported.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is a periodic weather-disrupting condition in the
tropical Pacific in which westward-blowing trade winds weaken,
allowing a mass of warm water to drive east to South America. The
name is Spanish for baby Jesus because the huge, warm pool usually
arrives around Christmas.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, El Nino will make itself known by the
"intensity, frequency and location" of winter storms expected to
lash the southern tier of states from California to Florida from
mid-December to January, meteorologists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
