<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Complains About Exporting Raw Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- President Yoweri Museveni is
unhappy with the export of raw materials, particularly coffee,
saying Uganda is being fleeced by developed countries, local
newspaper the Crusader reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Finance Minister Mayanja Nkangi, he mentioned a
cabinet meeting on November 3 when he showed three samples of
instant coffee: the first sample of 100 grams in a plastic
container of Uganda origin but processed abroad costs 14 U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The second of 100 grams from Colombia he showed in a glass
container costs seven U.S. Dollars in Britain, and the third of
250 grams in a paper container of Uganda origin costs seven U.S.
Dollars in France.
</P>
<P>
Uganda coffee is exported at a price of three Dollars a
kilogram.
</P>
<P>
In the letter dated November 12, the president told the
minister that developed countries earn 20 times more from the
processing than Uganda as the raw coffee exporter.
</P>
<P>
"We need to control this flabbergasting situation of value
lost" to the developed countries, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
Museveni described the coffee deal as "massive robbery,"
adding that Uganda also loses employment opportunities and other
services "through this processing of coffee abroad."
</P>
<P>
"The so-called least developed countries are characterized by
massive under-diversification of export potential," the president
noted.
</P>
<P>
He appealed for an end to the "slavery role of Uganda," saying
Uganda must export processed goods and have related bilateral
arrangements with China, India, Russia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Museveni urged the finance minister to speed up work in this
regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
