<HEADLINE> Vietnam Can Avert Crisis by Stepping Up Reform: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Vietnamese banking
official said his country can minimize the impact of the Asian
currency crisis by stepping up its own economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Le Duc Thuy, deputy governor of the State Bank of Vietnam, made
the remark in a statement carried by today's "Vietnam News" daily
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Thuy's statement, issued after a two-day regional seminar on
the Asian currency crisis, said that "Vietnam has so far been
relatively little affected by the crisis."
</P>
<P>
The State Bank of Vietnam, the Central Institute for Economic
Management and the Asian Development Bank held the seminar this
week to review the crisis and assess its impact on Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
But Thuy added that Vietnam's policy makers are to meet various
challenges as the country carries on reform to liberalize its
economy and intergrate it further with the global economy.
</P>
<P>
The seminar's objectives were to analyze the background of the
regional currency crisis from a technical and policy perspective
and to exchange information and help Vietnam's policy makers order
the country's priorities on economic reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
