<HEADLINE> Punishment Proposed for Road Barricade in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Obstructing rail, road and
waterway communications in Bangladesh is a criminal offense under
a proposed bill, seeking a maximum punishment of death sentence
for this, according to sources from the Home Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A draft bill in this regard, which was prepared by the Ministry
of Home Affairs and approved by the cabinet about three weeks ago,
will be placed before the parliament in its next session, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Titled the Prevention of Violence Against Women and Children
and Anti-Terrorism Bill, the bill seeks to replace the Women and
Children Repression Act, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Death penalty or life imprisonment or rigorous imprisonment
ranging from seven to 14 years may be awarded to anyone found
guilty obstructing rail, road and waterway communication, setting
fire to installations of power and telecommunication, moveable and
immovable property of government, autonomous, non-government
organizations and embassies, the bill says.
</P>
<P>
The bill says, a maximum punishment of death penalty or life
imprisonment with a fine of 100,000 taka (2,220 U.S. dollars) may
be awarded to anyone found guilty of attempting to kill or of
killing a child or woman with explosive materials.
</P>
<P>
About crimes relating to trafficking of women and children,
abduction of women, rape and dowry, the bill says, "death penalty
or life imprisonment with fine may be awarded to anyone found
guilty of inducing women in prostitution, adultery and flesh
trading.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
