<HEADLINE> Mozambique Rejects Swazi Territorial Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Ambassador to
Swaziland Lopes Ndelane today rejected a claim that his country's
Maputo province should revert to Swaziland, South African Press
Association reported from Mbabane.
</P>
<P>
Ndelane was reacting to claims made in the Swazi parliament
last week by Senator Prince Khuzulwandle that Maputo province in
southern Mozambique was Swazi territory.
</P>
<P>
Khuzulwandle is chairman of a border adjustment committee
pursuing Swaziland's claim for the reintegration of territories
to which it is laying claim but are now part of adjoining states.
</P>
<P>
Khuzulwandle told the Senate last week that Maputo province
was Swazi land which was leased to Mozambique under an agreement
between the Portuguese and British colonial governments.
</P>
<P>
Ndelane said Mozambicans had fought the Portuguese to get
their land back and if Swaziland felt it had any claim to parts
of Mozambique, it should have joined in the independence war
against the Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
He said Swaziland was also a signatory to an Organization of
African Unity (OAU) charter which declared that countries'
borders should remain as they were at independence.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also rejected territorial claims of Swaziland
over part of South Africa's Mpumalanga province.
</P>
<P>
South African Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi also
cited the OAU charter, saying that the issue of boundaries has
been settled long ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
