<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature: Election Envoys Come Knocking for Voters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The curtain rose on the first
Legislative Council elections in Hong Kong today as the actors
began their performance on the stage -- over 30,000 young election
ambassadors started knocking at voters' doors.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), Tung Chee Hwa, officiated a ceremony this noon in
the Hong Kong Park to kick off the 1998 Legislative Council
Election Voter Registration Week.
</P>
<P>
Some 900 representatives of the five teams of over 30,000 Voter
Registration Ambassadors were sworn in at the ceremony by Tung by
taking the "Voter Registration Oath", saying: "I will do my best
in helping voters in registration."
</P>
<P>
Later, the electoral roll will be split into the five
geographical constituencies in the SAR -- "New Territories East,"
"New Territories West," Kowloon East, Kowloon West and Hong Kong
Island.
</P>
<P>
Most of the ambassadors will visit homes in their own
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
The young envoys, teenagers, came from schools and universities
across the SAR.
</P>
<P>
"It's very good civic education for them. They can participate
in a way in managing Hong Kong affairs and learn something
about the electoral system," an official of the SAR government
said.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 voter registration supervisors, mostly teachers but
 also a small number of civil servants, are overseeing the work of
the ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Tung said: "The elections of the first
Legislative Council of the SAR is the first large-scale elections
in Hong Kong since it returned to the motherland on July 1, 1997.
We, the masters of our own affairs now, can and will make the
elections fair, open and right, so as to reflect the spirit of
'one country, two systems' and to realize the promise of 'Hong
Kong people governing Hong Kong'."
</P>
<P>
He also urged all Hong Kong people to actively participate in
the registration process and, later, the final voting.
</P>
<P>
To lend support to today's event, a number of senior SAR
government officials, including Administrative Secretary Anson
Chan, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang, Justice Secretary Elsie
Leung, Home Affairs Secretary David Lan and Constitutional Affairs
 Secretary Michael Suen, attended the ceremony and were on hand
to see off the ambassadors in their departure for their first
round of home visits.
</P>
<P>
Five ceremonial lions performed auspicious dances for the five
teams of ambassadors, who were also presented with colorful
banners.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the ceremony, Home Affairs Secretary Lan,
together with a team of the ambassadors, left the Hong Kong Park
for Yiu Tung Estate in Shau Kei Wan, Hong Kong Island, on board an
open-top bus to urge eligible residents to register for elections.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, which aims to make the electoral roll as complete
as possible in time for next May's legislative elections, is "a
formidable task" in Hong Kong with more than two million
households, a SAR government official said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors, mobilized by the Home Affairs Department of
the SAR government, are scheduled to make about two million
door-to-door visits during the voter registration week starting
today to register as many voters as possible.
</P>
<P>
They will fill in the forms for the voters, who will have to
put their signatures on the bottom line. "Everything will be
completed at their doorstep," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The deadline of the entire registration process is the middle
of next January.
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters, a bashful student-ambassador said: "I do
like the work, not only because Hong Kong is my home, but also
because I can learn much more in this campaign."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
