<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao-Taiwan Ocean Shipping Reports Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The ocean cargo shipping business
between Macao and Taiwan has reported profit for the first time
this year since it was launched in 1994, the Macao Daily News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The profit was due to better management and Macao's higher
demand of Taiwan goods, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Jointly run by the Ka-Ho Ocean Shipping Terminal, the Nam Kwang
Group Company and shipping companies from Taiwan, the Macao-Taiwan
cargo shipping service was launched in June 1994. But a total loss
of more than 10 million patacas (about 1.26 million US dollars)
had been made by the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The company started a reshuffle in mid-1996 to cut its shipping
costs. It also stopped renting containers and bought its own, and
lowered its maintenance costs by more than 2 million patacas
(253,000 US dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June this year, the company has stepped out of
the red, and its profits began rising in July.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the company's ship sails five times a month,
carrying an average of 140 containers on each shipping. That is
above 70 percent of its shipping capacity. It carried only about
60 containers on each sail in the beginning.
</P>
<P>
The report said that shipping business grows because Macao's
demand for Taiwan products has risen over the past year. About 70
percent of the goods from Taiwan are for sale in Macao instead of
re-exporting to China's inland.
</P>
<P>
The future business growth, however, is not optimistic, the
report quoted experts as saying. Unless Macao's population has
sharp increase and the living standard in Macao and the
neighboring Pearl River Delta is remarkably improved, there will
be no big increase in shipping.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
