<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners to Dominate Thai Finance Sector: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Finance Minister
Pisit Leeahtam has revealed that Thailand's financial sector will
be dominated largely by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
He said on Friday that he was saddened that Thailand could no
longer take pride in the financial system it had built up over the
last 50 years, as mergers and takeovers of Thai finance firms by
foreign financial institutions at this stage have become
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
Now it was time for Thai institutions to swallow their pride
and survive, Pisit said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government is scheduled to announce on Monday the fate
of the 58 finance firms suspended by the Chavalit Yongchaiyudh
administration in June and August.
</P>
<P>
An overwhelming majority of the 58 firms are expected to close
down, leaving no more than five to reopen.
</P>
<P>
The 58 finance firms were suspended because of their financial
mismanagement resulting in massive bad debts and a lack of
liquidity.
</P>
<P>
A few foreign takeover bids have been reported, but so far no
confirmation has been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police have been put on alert at the suspended
finance firms to prevent untoward incidents which might happen
after the announcement on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A decision on the future of the 58 suspended companies has long
been seen as an important step in restoring public and investor
confidence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
