<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Canada Estimated to Have 3.8 Million Problem Gamblers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A new study estimates that
3.8 million adults in the United States and Canada suffer from
serious gambling disorder.
</P>
<P>
It means an increase of more than 1.6 million since casino and
lotteries exploded across America two decades ago, said the study
conducted by Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
As if echoing the study, a survey released this week found that
gambling is the first concern of the Chinese American community
in San Francisco. Seventy percent of the 1,808 adults of Chinese
origin surveyed said that gambling is a big problem, which is
often connected with bankruptcy, loan-sharking and domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
All U.S. states except Utah and Hawaii offer some form of legal
gambling, from lotteries and horse lottery to slot machines and
blackjack. Casino gambling is legal in 26 states. Internet makes
it easier to bet from home on the computer.
</P>
<P>
Harvard researchers analyzed data on gambling addiction
published between 1977 and 1997. They estimated that almost 1.3
percent of adults who gamble are "pathological gamblers," up from 0.84
percent in 1993. It is believed there is a much greater number of
people with less-severe gambling problems.
</P>
<P>
The American Psychiatric Association describes "pathological
gambling" as an impulse-control disorder. More specifically, one
medical doctor says that compulsive pathological gambling is a
progressive disorder characterized by a continuous or periodic
loss of control over gambling, a preoccupation with gambling and
continuation of the behavior despite adverse consequences.
</P>
<P>
Describing his experience on Internet, a former gambler said
that compulsive gambling is something to the point where there is
no distinction between right and wrong, day and night or day to day.
</P>
<P>
According to the Harvard researchers, the growth in compulsive
gambling among adults is linked to the emergence of gambling as an
acceptable part of American's entertainment culture, where casinos
are advertised as family resorts and lotteries are touted by
governments as the path to easy millions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0109 </DOCNO>
