<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bumper Grain Harvest for Jiangsu Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Jiangsu Province is expected to
reap a record-high 35 billion kilograms of grain this year.
</P>
<P>
Latest prediction shows that the province's grain output is to
total 35.64 billion kilograms, a rise of 2.5 percent over last
year.
</P>
<P>
As part of the achievements, counties which have an average of
400 kilograms of wheat per mu (15 mu equals to one hectare) and
townships which have an average of 500 kilograms of wheat per mu
have emerged for the first time in history.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials attributed the bumper grain harvest to
consistent government policy encouraging the development of
farming.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of this year, the province had
injected 1.19 billion yuan (143.37 million US dollars) in
agriculture, a year-on-year increase of 98.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The application of new technology and scientific methods have
also been of great help to farming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renewed Communal Clash Kills 15 in W. Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 6 (Xinhua) -- About 15 people were feared dead
with tens of others injured in the latest clash between Ife and
Modakeke communities in west Nigeria's Osun state over the past
four days.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fightings were still going on in several areas as at
3:00 p.m. Friday afternoon, while the efforts of police to put
out the fire of burning houses continued to be frustrated by the
non-functional fire fighting unit, according to press reports
today.
</P>
<P>
Commercial activities were completely paralyzed in the
communities as major roads were completed deserted.
</P>
<P>
While armed police were busy dispersing the militant youths
from the face-to-face battle, Osun state administrator Anthony
Obi was in the two communities Friday afternoon to monitor the
situation.
</P>
<P>
The new round of clash, in a series triggered off by the
relocation of local government headquarters from Madakeke to
Ike-Ogbo in Ile-Ife area earlier this year, broke out last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the state government said it would proceed
with the State House of Assembly polls due today in the feuding
communities of Ife and Modakeke.
</P>
<P>
But it has become impossible to go ahead with the election due
to the tense situation arising from the fresh bloodshed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
