<HEADLINE> 3 Lebanese Civilians Killed in Explosions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Three Lebanese civilians were
killed and another was wounded Friday night in a series of
explosions in south Lebanon, Lebanese radio Voice of the People
reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Maas, 55, a shepherd, was tending his flock on the
slopes of Wadi Salouqi, 400 meters below the village of Majdal
Slim, on the edge of the Israeli-occupied zone in south Lebanon,
when he was killed in an explosion.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Alaeddine, 17, and Qassem Maas, both relatives of Maa,
were also killed in another series of blasts as they tried to
recover the shepherd's body. Rafiq Zahwa, who accompanied them,
was wounded.
</P>
<P>
It is unclear whether the explosions came from roadside bombs
or land mines.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese newspaper the Daily Star said that Wadi Salouqi is
an important route used by the resistance forces to infiltrate
into the central sector of the 1,200 square kilometers buffer
zone occupied by Israel since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Israeli forces regularly plant land mines and road side bombs
in the area to target the resistance fighters. Last summer two
children were wounded by land mines in the same area.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah's (Party of God) southern commander Sheikh Nabil
Qaouk condemned the killings.
</P>
<P>
"We hold the Zionist enemy fully responsible for this crime
and everything that will follow it," he told reporters.
"The event will not pass without severe punishment," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
