<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flexible Policy Helps Zhangjiajie Attract Funds to Develop Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Zhangjiajie, a major tourist
city in central China, has attracted about five billion yuan
(602.4 million US dollars) in building tourist facilities thanks
to flexible policies.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie in Hunan Province is famous for Wulingyuan Scenic
and Historical Site Area-- a unique mountain resort which is on the
world heritage list of UNESCO. However, development of tourist
facilities were constantly delayed or interrupted in the past by
lack of funds, partly due to a rigid investment policy practised
by the government.
</P>
<P>
As the reform deepened, the local government has become more
flexible in absorbing investment, including overseas financing.
</P>
<P>
As a result, it only took 11 months for a Hong Kong investor to
add a 80 million-yuan (9.638 million US dollars) cableway on the
scenic Tianzi Mountain.
</P>
<P>
Another investor from Hong Kong spent 30 million yuan to build a
high-grade highway, which opened to traffic in August, linking two
major scenic areas.
</P>
<P>
The local government also leased the Baofeng Lake Park to a
Malaysian investor, who has turned the previous money-loser into a
profit-maker by investing 25 million yuan in it.
</P>
<P>
As a major fund-raising breakthrough, the city has successfully
listed the scenic area on the domestic stock market. The public
listing marked the first stock of China's travel industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
