<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Hopes Better Ties with Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa has expressed the hope that the relations between Cairo
and Tehran would reach the highest level, local daily Iran News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"I hope mutual relations between Iran and Egypt will reach
their highest level," Moussa said Friday upon his arrival here
for the foreign ministers' meeting of the eighth Organization of
Islamic Conference (OIC) to be opened this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said that Egypt and Iran maintained their contacts and
consultations despite the fact that there are no diplomatic
relations between the two Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran severed diplomatic ties with Egypt soon after Egypt
signed the David Camp peace accords with Israel in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that grounds existed between the two countries
for understanding and for dialogue, adding that the existence of
differences between the two countries was natural and it does not
necessarily mean the existence of tension or negative attitudes
between Cairo and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic about the future," he said, stressing that
"as I have repeatedly said, relation with Iran is very important
for us."
</P>
<P>
With the deadlock of the Middle East peace process due to the
hardline policies of the Israeli Likud government, Iran and Egypt
are getting closer in recent months and there is some speculation
here that it is possible for the two countries to resume ties in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
Local dailies and some Iranian officials expressed the hope
that Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak would be able to attend
the OIC summit to be opened Tuesday, paving the way for the
rapprochement between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
