<HEADLINE> Shaanxi Tourism to Focus on Folklore in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Shaanxi Province, home of
"Terra-cotta warriors," will offer colorful folklore programs to
overseas tourists in the coming 1998, sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, which is being promoted on international market, is
designed to respond to a national theme for the travel industry
entitled "98 China City and Country Tour."
</P>
<P>
To provide a chance for overseas tourists to live in a cave
dwelling on the Loess plateau will be a highlight.
</P>
<P>
After visiting the terra-cotta soldiers, known as the "eighth
wonders of the world" and the Forest of Steles in Xi'an, the
provincial capital, travelers can go to and live in a cave
dwelling of a local farmer, not only to enjoy coolness in summer
and warmth in winter, but also to discover a mysterious oriental
culture extending several thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
Over 90 kilometers northwest of Xi'an, near the mausoleum of
Wuzetian, an empress of the Tang Dynasty (618-907) and the only
empress in China's history, one can find a folklore culture
village jointly built by investors from China and the Republic of
Korea.
</P>
<P>
Covering 26,000 square meters, the attraction offers a chance
for visitors to participate in local crafts such as paper-making
and weaving.
</P>
<P>
Other programs of the year include watching local operas,
cock-fighting, and variety shows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
