<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Police Urged to Preserve Rule of Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Elsie Leung Oi-sie, secretary
for justice of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
government, today called on the police to continue to contribute
to Hong Kong's top priority of preserving the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government is committed to the rule of law which
dictates that no one is above the law, Leung said at the police
passing-out parade ceremony held at the Police Training School
today.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the wide powers given to police officers to enable them
to carry out their duties must be exercised in strict accordance
with the law.
</P>
<P>
Another aspect of the rule of law is that legal powers must not
be exercised arbitrarily, or be the subject of improper influence,
she said.
</P>
<P>
"The decisions that you make, as police officers, must be based
on the merits of the case, not on who is involved, or how rich, or
influential or well-connected he or she may be," she said.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that police officers could not successfully carry
out their duties without the support and confidence of the
community.
</P>
<P>
The growing involvement by the community in fighting crime is a
reflection of the esteem in which the Police Force is held.
</P>
<P>
She called on the force not to undermine this support by
behavior that would alienate members of the public and every
member of the force must strive to meet the rising expectations of
the community.
</P>
<P>
The Police Force can earn the respect of local people only when
they are polite, helpful and patient, she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"This is particularly true for Police officers, who are
constantly dealing with members of the public, often in stressful
situations," she said.
</P>
<P>
She praised the Police Force who has earned its reputation for
excellence through the dedication and professionalism of its
officers, and its commitment to the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
She called on the graduating officers to help preserve that
reputation and pledged the continued support of the Department of
Justice to the Police in the maintenance of law and order.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 inspectors and 101 police constables graduated at
today's parade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
