<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Calls for Cooperation in Flood Forecasting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Water Resources
Minister Abdur Razzak has called on neighboring countries to
cooperate in facilitating flood forecasting and warning in the
region, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
He made the call here Friday at a two-day international seminar
attended by about 40 water and flood forecasting experts from
Bangladesh, India, Nepal, Bhutan, France, the United Kingdom and
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The four South Asian countries especially want to seek
cooperation in forecasting floods in the Ganges, the Brahmaputra
and the Meghna river basins, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the seminar, which was organized by the Bangladesh
National Committee of International Commission on Irrigation and
Drainage, Abdur Razzak urged the countries in the basins to work
together to improve their present system of flood forecasting and
warning.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is highly vulnerable to regular and often
devastating floods, the minister said. "It needs to protect its
people and property from this continual hazard."
</P>
<P>
On flood management, he said the question to be solved by the
planners now is what degree of protection is practicable,
affordable and justifiable in terms of structural and
non-structural measures.
</P>
<P>
He said another aspect that demands due consideration is the
prospect of reducing flood intensities in the downstream of the
three rivers through regulating flood flows in their upper
catchments.
</P>
<P>
The minister said such regulation through upstream storage of
monsoon flows would significantly augment the dry season flows of
these rivers to ease the water availability situation in the
critical dry months in all the countries in the basins.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
