<HEADLINE> Medical Care Reform Eases National Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- All provinces, municipalities
and autonomous regions in China have introduced a reform scheme
under which State subsidies only pay part of people's medical
expenses, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
For example, since October 3, patients in Beijing who had been
enjoying free health care can only prescribe from 1,156 types of
medicines. Cost of medicines not on the list will not be
reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
The central government in 1951 declared free health care for
people. This covered nearly all urban residents.
</P>
<P>
More than four decades later, the free health care system has
become a major financial burden for the government and State
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The biggest problem is the rapid rise of costs for free medical
care, although it was not purely "free" because patients have been
required to pay five to 20 percent of medical costs since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
"The medical care reform now undergoing in China is expected to
ease the heavy burden nationwide," an official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Slows Designing Long-legged 777 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Boeing has slowed design
work on the new 10,000-mile-nonstop model of its 777 airliner
because it has received no firm orders after six months of
marketing.
</P>
<P>
Another proposed model, the Boeing 747-500/600, was dropped
early this year.
</P>
<P>
The company began seeking customers for the 200-seat,
two-engined jetliner, called the 777-200/300X, earlier this year,
and hoped to launch development by the end of the year and deliver
the first aircraft in late 2000.
</P>
<P>
So far only Malaysian Airlines Systems (MLA) has expressed its
intention of buying the new model. But the Malaysian government's
planned spending cuts might affect the purchase.
</P>
<P>
Many of the potential buyers of the new model are airlines in
Asia, where economic problems are slowing traffic and profits.
</P>
<P>
In addition, rival Airbus Industries has captured commitments
for about 50 of its new four-engine A340s to go into service in
2002 or 2003. The new plane is priced at about 150 million
U.S. dollars and its engines are already in service, which makes
it cheaper than the 777X.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing long-range model, expected to be sold at a price of
up to 170 million dollars per airplane, will require new and
larger engines. The company has to consider reducing costs of both
manufacturing and operations.
</P>
<P>
President of Boeing Commercial Airplane Group, Ron Woodard,
said earlier this week that a launch of the new 777 model remains
a possibility. "It's up for the customers to say where we are," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Official Calls for Preparations for Tougher Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Thai deputy prime minister
Bhichai Rattakul has urged the Thai people to prepare for even
tougher times in the next three to six months, predicting that the
country's economic crisis will bottom out after that period.
</P>
<P>
"We will face more hardship in the next three to six months
because the situation has not reached its low-point," the Nation
newspaper today quotes Bhichai as saying on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The people will have to be more patient," he said, adding that
the government will eventually be able to solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
He blamed external factors for the Thai currency's all-time low
last week.
</P>
<P>
Up to December 4, the baht had lost a staggering 65 percent of
its value against the dollar in five months since its float on
July 2. On Wednesday, it dropped to 43.05 against the dollar, and
dealers will not rule out a further decline in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Bhichai expressed the belief that the people will be fully
cooperative with the government in its efforts to revive the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, top officials of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and deputy prime minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, who
oversees the country's economy, expressed similar optimism about
the bottom-out. However, private sector analysts, including
commercial bank executives, believe that it will take at least two
years for the country's economy to see an upturn.  
</P>
</TEXT>
