<HEADLINE> Russia, Ukraine to Build Strategic Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
said today that the Ukrainian-Russian treaty on friendship and
partnership signed in May would lead to a strategic partnership
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said that he believed the treaty he signed with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin would be approved by the two parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Ukrainian Supreme Soviet Alexander Moroz held
talks in Moscow this month with leaders of Russia's Duma (the
lower house) and federal council (the upper house) on an early
approval of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said that Russia and Ukraine should set up closer
relations in all aspects.
</P>
<P>
He said that obstacles between the two countries had brought
great loss to the bilateral economic relations. Since Russia
imposed a dual value-added tax upon imports from Ukraine in May
1996, Ukraine's trade had suffered a loss of three billion hryvnas
(about 1.596 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In mid-November, Kuchma and Yeltsin agreed that Russia would
exempt imports from Ukraine from dual value-added tax as from
January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said a short and long-term cooperation plan would be
signed between the two countries during his coming visit to
Russia. It would be a detailed and practical one covering
economy, science and technology and culture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
