<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Government to Conduct Economic Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Union government
plans to conduct a nation-wide economic census to evaluate the
impact of its economic reforms since 1991, official sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
A proposal in this regard by the Department of Statistics has
already been approved by the Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs
(CCEA) and the idea is to enumerate all enterprises engaged in
economic activities except the agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
The census, which will cover both urban and rural enterprises,
will collect information on enterprises and their location, type
of activity and nature of operation. The survey will provide
information for planning and policy formulation.
</P>
<P>
The economic census will also draw a sample frame for detailed
surveys of unorganized activities. These sample surveys will
provide information on investments, capital structure, employment,
input consumption, product output, services and other economic
characteristics like the ratio of entrepreneurial activities in
the unorganized sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian to Open Green Channel for Electronic Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 6 (Xinhua)-- The Indian government has
decided to open a green channel for exporters of electronic goods
by simplifying import and export clearance procedures to help them
execute orders at short notice, a government official said today.
</P>
<P>
Under the new facility, Indian exporters of electronic goods
can avoid delays by opting for "self declaration" with regard to
the quantity, value and the duty rate of goods imported.
</P>
<P>
The exporters could therefore clear their import consignments
quickly, send them to the production line and ship their export
consignments without any delay.
</P>
<P>
This facility is necessary for boosting electronics sector
exports as Indian exporters import most of the components for
manufacturing hardware. The "self declaration" option will be
available in the case of export clearance too.
</P>
<P>
To check misuse, the Customs Department will conduct random
audit and verify if exporters are evading customs duty.
</P>
<P>
The facility will be introduced on an experimental basis first.
If it works properly, the procedures will be put in use on a
long-term basis.
</P>
<P>
Electronics is the first sector set to benefit from the "real"
green channel facility, which would also be introduced to the
garments sector if it proves to be successful.
</P>
<P>
Exporters from various sectors have complained that procedural
hassles take up much of their time and delay execution of export
orders. They have demanded a streamlining of procedures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0145 </DOCNO>
