<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Temporary Software Programmers to Lose Overtime Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. state of
Washington has made a new labor law that could save companies such
as Microsoft and Boeing millions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rule, time-and-a-half pay for thousands of
software-industry professionals working under hourly contract
would be eliminated, reported the Seattle Times.
</P>
<P>
Software companies and other corporations such as Boeing often
hire temporary workers for short-term projects which require large
amount of overtime on jobs. It is estimated that Microsoft alone
hires about 5,000 contract workers, nearly one-third of its Seattle
work force.
</P>
<P>
The new rule will only apply to higher pay ranks. As written,
the rule would exempt from overtime "any employee who is a
computer system analyst, computer programmer, software developer
or other similar skilled worker" who has experience and
theoretical knowledge of computers.
</P>
<P>
The state Department of Labor and Industries has set February 1
as the tentative date for implementing the change.
</P>
<P>
Those affected employees would be paid "straight time" for
extra hours, while those earning under $27.63 per hour would still
receive the overtime premium. Most software programmers earn 40
or 50 dollars an hour.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal law was changed in 1995 to exempt software
professionals from overtime rules. Most other states already have
adopted the change, which gives employees and employers more
flexibility in scheduling work hours.
</P>
<P>
Usually, employers like to let contract employees work 60 or 70
hours at a stretch and then take a few days off, a work pattern
some employees also prefer.
</P>
<P>
But there are contract workers who do not have security of
benefit such as health insurance. Overtime pay is actually a
tradeoff for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
