<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30 Clearing, Forwarding Firms Suspended in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Revenue Authority
(KRA) has suspended the operations of 30 clearing and forwarding
agents in the Indian Ocean port of Mombasa in fight with imports
under the name of transit goods, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agents have failed to account for the transit goods they
cleared in the past eight months and their operating licenses
will not be renewed until they pay the outstanding customs duty,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Most of these companies listed cleared goods including cars,
second-hand clothes and electronics which are believed to be in
the local market although they left the port as transit cargo in
order to avoid paying customs duty, said the authority.
</P>
<P>
So far these agents have not confirmed to the revenue body
that the goods actually left the country as indicated on the
entry form.
</P>
<P>
However, Owen Magotti, a director of Lions Export and Import
Agencies Ltd., which is on the list of the suspended companies,
said he would take the KRA to court for suspending his
operations.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the clearing and forwarding agents were not to
blame for the non-payment of duty, and accused the go-down owners
of releasing the goods to their owners without the knowledge of
the clearing agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
