<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smuggled Falcons Released Back to Wild </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A total of 40 falcons
confiscated from smugglers were released back to the wild in
Beijing Mangshan National Forest Park yesterday, today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Only one of them failed to fly away and will be cared for by
the park. Most of others are expected to return to their home in
northwest China.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time of wild release this year by the
Beijing Forestry Bureau (BFB) and Beijing Customs. On the first
occasion, a number of falcons were released in the Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Yang Dehong, senior official at BFB said more seized falcons
will be released when they are fit enough.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Customs have seized 94 smuggled falcons since late
August, including 32 discovered in a case last week. They are
temporarily being taken care of by the Beijing Zoo and the Beijing
Endangered Animal Breeding Center.
</P>
<P>
Smugglers, some from abroad, started their activities earlier
than normal this year, commencing in mid-August rather than
October as in the past, according to Wang Minzhong, vice-director
of the bureau's Wildlife Protection Station.
</P>
<P>
They have also broadened their channels and adopted more
duplicitous measures to smuggle the falcons, classified as rare
birds under State class two protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
