<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Names Medicare Reform Appointees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
named his appointees on Friday to the 17-member commission on
keeping Medicare -- the federal health insurance program --
solvent beyond baby-boomer retirements.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Republicans in Congress are now stuck in a
stalemate over naming a chairman.
</P>
<P>
The bipartisan panel, by statute, was to have been in place by
December 1.
</P>
<P>
Of the candidates mentioned for the chairman of the commission,
Senator John Breaux, a Democrat, has surfaced as the leading
contender, Republican aides said. House Republicans remain
concerned about a Democrat taking the chairmanship and are
insisting on a Republican co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
Under the statute that created the commission, the chairman is
to be decided by the mutual consent of Clinton, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott and House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
Announcing his appointments outside the Oval Office, Clinton
said: "I look forward to their proposals to keep Medicare at the
core of the American dream in the new century.
</P>
<P>
"We have an obligation to strengthen it for the next century,
to ensure that it is as strong for our children as it has been for
our parents and to ensure that the baby boomers have access to
quality, affordable health care when we retire."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Republican Senator Phil Gramm said: "I hope we can
conclude quickly that raising taxes to rescue Medicare just won't
work."
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt made the
final two appointments.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Gingrich and Lott announced their eight
members. Gingrich asked each of his four appointments to promise
not to consider tax increases as a way to rescue the health
insurance program that covers about 37 million elderly and
disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton did not extract such a commitment from his
nominees, spokesman Mike McCurry said, because he didn't want to
tie the hands of the commission.
</P>
<P>
Medicare is expected to begin running deficits as the baby boom
generation begins retiring in about a decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
