<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Suggests Increase in Iraqi Oil Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia is advocating that the
amount of the Iraqi oil exported, in exchange for humanitarian
food and medical supplies over another six months, should be
raised to four billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the Russian Foreign Ministry, Gennady
Tarasov, made the observation at a news conference after the
United Nations passed the Number 1143 resolution, which extended
the oil-for-food plan for another six months.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov said the report UN Secretary General, Kofi Annan,
submitted to the Security Council, showed that the Iraqis had been
living without enough food, basic medicines and medical equipment,
and the death rate had risen.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government paid great attention to the serious
crisis in Iraq, Tarasov said.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia regarded the Number 1143 resolution as a interim
one, which could provide the possibility of improving the
humanitarian plan. It was also the prelude for discussing the
implementment to the oil-for-food deal by the end of 1998, Tarasov
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Hits Record Low of 4,020 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah breached
the 4,000 level against the U.S. dollar for the first time in
afternoon trade on Friday in response to the latest slump in
regional currencies, dealers here said today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, Bank Indonesia, stepped in several times to
provide some support to the rupiah, but failed to reverse the
trend as the South Korean won tumbled and the Japanese yen
followed, said the dealers.
</P>
<P>
They said the drop in the rupiah was not only driven by a
combination of regional weaknesses but also by an increasing
dollar demand from the indebted local corporations.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah, which opened at 3,930/50, touched a new historic
low of 4,020 against the dollar in spot market during a lunch
break despite a market intervention by the central bank in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
The currency recovered slightly to close at 3,970/90 following
a rebound in the Malaysian ringgit, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The value of the rupiah against the dollar has dropped by about
50 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the stock market was unperturbed, jumping 3.2 percent
to close at 414.78 points -- its second straight day of gain.
</P>
<P>
Brokers described Friday's gain as a short-term technical
rebound, supported by the rise of the regional stock markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
