<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Six Palestinians were wounded Friday during a
clash in the Gaza Strip with Israeli soldiers who fired live
bullets to disperse Palestinian protesters in a land dispute.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio and state television Channel I quoted Palestinian
sources as reporting that the clash occurred during a
demonstration held by hundreds of Palestinians, who protested an
alleged Israeli plan to set up a military outpost on a disputed
hilltop near Rafaih. (Israel-Palestine-Clashes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union is launching two high-level
policy advice projects worth 6 million ECUs (6.7 million
U.S. dollars) to support Russia's reforms.
</P>
<P>
The assistance program, announced here Friday by the European
Commission, will be directed at strengthening the building up of a
state of law by supporting local institutions involved in legal
reforms and at providing the Russian administration with
high-level economic policy advice. (EU-Aid-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The American space shuttle Columbia returned to
its home port in Florida on Friday morning after a 16-day space
science mission, ending the eighth and final flight of the year.
</P>
<P>
Columbia and its six crew members swooped through a clear,
chilly sky and landed safely on the runway at the Kennedy Space
Center. Mission control officials greeted the astronauts and
congratulated their successful journey which covered some 104
million-kilometers. (US-Shuttle-Landing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Federal drug agents have seized three
methamphetamine labs and arrested 100 people on charges of
producing and distributing the drug in the United States.
</P>
<P>
James Milford, deputy administrator of the Drug Enforcement
Administration (DEA), told a news conference Friday that those
charged were strongly connected to and got precursor chemicals
from the Amezcua-Contreras gang, which U.S. officials believe is
the largest Mexican meth gang. (US-Drug-Ring)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Only 10 percent of the humanitarian supplies under the
U.N. oil-for-food deal has been distributed, an Iraqi minister was
on Friday quoted by Egypt's Middle East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with the news agency, Minister of Trade of
Iraq Mohamed Mehdi Saleh was complaining of the slow distribution
of food and medicine to the Iraqi people during the first two
phases of the deal. (Iraq-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton said on Friday the Middle
East peace process should be pushed forward with "some new ideas".
</P>
<P>
Speaking with reporters at the White House, Clinton said
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had brought these ideas to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat when she met Netanyahu in Paris on Friday and Arafat
in Geneva on Saturday. (US-Mideast) 
</P>
