<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IWF Toughen Its Position on Doping As Games Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The International Weightlifting
Federation (IWF) held the annual congress on Friday at Chiang Mai,
Thailand, poised to take a tough line on doping at the upcoming
world championships.
</P>
<P>
The IWF congress decided to inflict collective punishment on
national teams whose members were found out to have abused banned
substances.
</P>
<P>
"For example, if a country has six athletes qualified for the
games, but has two previous doping cases, it will have only four
participants for the Olympic Games," said IWF secretary general
Tamas Ajan.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general said the congress also agreed to include
cannabis in the IWF doping list at the eight-day world
championships to be opened at Chiang Mai on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"For the first offence, the athlete will have a six months
suspension. The second time, it will be a life suspension." said
Tamas Ajan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
