<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Seek Foreign Help to Stop Hard Currency Outflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian legislators will ask
Western countries to track bank accounts opened by Ukrainians in
their countries to help Ukraine to control illegal outflows of
hard currency, a top Ukrainian politician said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Petro Simonenko, leader of the Ukrainian Communist Party and a
member of the Supreme Soviet (parliament), said at a press
conference that the Western countries will be urged to reveal
sources of Ukraine's hard currency deposited in the banks of those
countries.
</P>
<P>
The appeal, which have been signed by 151 Ukrainian
legislators, will be sent to governments and parliaments in
Britain, Canada, Germany, Switzerland, the United States and some
other countries.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government believes that at least 20 billion
U.S. dollars are illegally kept in foreign banks by Ukrainians
operating in the shadow economy.
</P>
<P>
Simonenko also said about 12 billion dollars and 45 to 60
percent of the Ukrainian currency, the hryvna, are circulating in
the country but out of the reach of Ukrainian banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
