<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Inflation to Remain Below 6 percent in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Despite the current financial
crisis and the devaluation of the peso, the Philippines' inflation
rate in 1997 could remain below 6 percent, said a senior finance
official.
</P>
<P>
The country is assured of a manageable price situation by
year-end despite the mild increase in the inflation rate from
October to November, Socio-Economic Planning Secretary Cielito
Habito said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
That was "consistent with expectation," Habito said, because
the November rate of 6.5 percent has brought the January to
November average to less than 5 percent, and is certain to keep
the full-year average at "well below our projected average of 6 to
6.5 percent."
</P>
<P>
Even the 0.6 percent month-on-month rise is consistent with the
average projected for the period, which is 0.6 to 0.7 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Statistics Office, the country's
inflation rate in November rose to 6.5 percent year-on-year,
compared to 5.7 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Habito's view was supported by Central Bank Governor Gabriel
Singson, who said the "whole year average inflation rate would be
less than 5.5 percent even if the December inflation rate rises to
12 percent."
</P>
<P>
The recent increase in oil prices and the 35 percent
devaluation of the peso in the last five months resulted in the
higher inflation rate in November, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
