<HEADLINE> C. America Fishing Businessmen Meet in Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of the board
of directors of the Central America Aquiculture and Fishing
Businessmen Organization (Oecap) opened here today to discuss the
ways to open more international markets.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the inauguration session, Nicaraguan President
Arnold that the fishing sector has become one of the most dynamic
sectors in the last few years, contributing greatly to the gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
He said that export of fishing products occupies the second
place in Nicaragua's total exports.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the isthmus six countries attended the
meeting and they discussed the volume of fishing production in
Central America, access to economic resources and other
fishing-related issues.
</P>
<P>
The value of the fishing production in the region reached 630
U.S. million dollars, 370 million dollars more than the 1990
figure.
</P>
<P>
The regional fishing industry fleet includes 985 ships, 70
percent of them capturing shrimp, and the rest for lobster,
sardines, snail and tuna, generating 500 million dollars a year in
hard currency. 
</P>
