<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Lessons From Southeast Asian Financial Crisis (1)  by Chen Hegao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1997 will be
remembered as an unfortunate one for both individuals and
governments in Southeast Asia, as the region has been devastated
by an unexpected financial crisis in the year.
</P>
<P>
For many individuals, their fortunes built up over many a year
crumbled before their eyes because of currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
For most governments, their economic achievements made in the
last decades were eliminated overnight by market turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Since the crisis began to hit the region in July, the
currencies of Thailand, the Philippines, Indonesia, Malaysia and
Singapore have depreciated between 10 and 35 percent. Stock
markets have also fallen to their lowest in years.
</P>
<P>
Economists painted a bleak picture of Southeast Asian
economies, which, they said, are likely to grow around 5 to 6
percent for this year and next, 2 or 3 percentage points lower
than last year.
</P>
<P>
The economic pains have triggered political instability in some
parts of the region, where protests against price hikes, bank
closures and layoffs have been frequent in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Amid strong protests against his government's failure to check
the crisis, Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh resigned in
November.
</P>
<P>
The shock wave also raged beyond the region. From Hong Kong to
Australia, from Japan to the United States, stock markets
experienced dramatic ups and downs in October. Now, South Korea
and Japan have been dragged into the crisis with market
turbulence.
</P>
<P>
What has happened to these "economic tigers" and why?
</P>
<P>
Some people, including government leaders, point the finger at
currency speculators. But many economists argue that common
financial risks created for many years in the region are the main
cause of the crisis though speculators should also be blamed.
</P>
<P>
From the crisis, policy makers, bankers, investors, businessmen
and economists can draw valuable lessons, which may help prevent
the recurrence of such crises.
</P>
<P>
According to economic analysts, a poorly managed and regulated
banking sector could aggravate financial risks by lending for
consumption and speculative purposes or by financing a structure
boom.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Southeast Asian banks enjoyed lending booms
while their loan-loss provisions fell. From 1994 to 1996, lending
by Philippine banks shot up 38 percent while provisioning for loan
losses dropped from 3.3 percent of total loans to just 1.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to boost profits, Southeast Asian banks extended
excessive loans to the property sector. Indonesian banks' exposure
to the property sector accounted for nearly 20 percent of their
total loans, Thailand and Malaysia about 18 percent and the
Philippines over 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The over-exposure to the property sector resulted in the
over-supply of office and residential buildings and a huge amount
of non-performing loans, which will peak through 1998 at 73
billion dollars in the region.
</P>
<P>
Financial risks created by non-performing loans forced Thailand
to close 58 financial institutions and Indonesia 16 commercial
banks during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
A lesson from the crisis is that as banks dominate financial
intermediation in developing countries, strict banking rules must
be worked out and implemented. Otherwise, these countries could
meet the same fate as Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Lessons From Southeast Asian Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Another important lesson drawn from the crisis is that
developing countries must adopt a flexible exchange rate system,
which should keep abreast of the economic development and
globalization in the world.
</P>
<P>
Before the crisis, Southeast Asian countries fixed exchange
rates for their currencies, which were pegged to the U.S. dollar.
But when the appreciation of the dollar vis-a-vis the Japanese yen
started in 1995, Southeast Asian countries did not change their
policy and instead kept the peg.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the dollar's appreciation led to the rapid
appreciation of Southeast Asian currencies, contributing to a
slowdown in exports of several Southeast Asian countries in 1996
and 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to World Bank economists, Thailand experienced a real
appreciation of 17 percent between 1995 and June 1997 compared
with 20 percent for the Philippines, 10 percent for Malaysia and 8
percent for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
During this period, Thailand saw the sharpest deterioration in
export performance. Thailand's exports in dollar terms were flat
in 1996 and the first half of 1997 while export receipts increased
by 5 percent annually in Malaysia and 9.5 percent in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The sharp decline in exports pushed up the current account
deficits of Thailand, the Philippines, Malaysia and Indonesia to a
range of between 4.6 percent and 9 percent of their gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
The third lesson from the crisis is that the economic structure
of developing countries should always be adapted to the changes of
the world market and economic growth cannot be sustained by
relying on the export of a single product.
</P>
<P>
But the economic structures of Southeast Asian countries are
too vulnerable to the constant changes of the world market as
these economies depend heavily on the export of electronic
products.
</P>
<P>
As electronic products accounted for around 40 percent of the
total exports in the region, the lower demand for electronics in
the United States and Europe last year cut down steeply the export
revenues of these countries.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that if Southeast Asian countries fail to
undertake economic adjustments, including the change of their
economic structures, they could suffer again whenever changes take
place in the world markets.
</P>
<P>
They called on countries in the region to develop more
high-tech products so as to bolster their economic
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the poor quality of investments in the region also
led to financial risks over the last few years. And this is the
fourth lesson for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
During the past decades, Southeast Asia was the fastest growing
region in the world, but countries in the region borrowed heavily
abroad to finance their development.
</P>
<P>
At present, foreign debts make up 40 percent of GDP for
Thailand, around 50 percent for the Philippines, 47 percent for
Indonesia and 39 percent for Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Of their foreign debts, about 25 percent are in the form of
short-term borrowings, most of which are speculative in nature.
</P>
<P>
Their reliance on foreign funds, and short-term debts in
particular, not only increased current account deficits but also
resulted in financial risks.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, the worst of the financial crisis in Southeast
Asia seems to be over, at least for now. The valuable lessons from
the five-month-old crisis may help both Southeast Asian nations
and other developing countries in avoiding financial risks in
their future development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
