<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguay's Tax Revenue Up 9.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Uruguay's tax revenue
increased 9.1 percent in the first 10 months of this year,
compared with the same period last year, the General Tax Revenue
Direction (TRD) said.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, value added tax, making up 53 percent of
the total tax revenue, was up 8.3 percent to the equivalent of
1.47 billion U.S. dollars. This increase was attributed to a
higher domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
Internal specific taxes showed a 10.3 percent real growth in
all lines while the tax on motor vehicles rose by 45.9
percent. The sales of vehicles were 20 percent more than last year.
</P>
<P>
Income tax on industry and commerce and the tax on patrimony,
which contribute 18 percent of the money to the TRD vaults, had a
growth of 8.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
