<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks Warned of Destabilizing Factors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. investment firm Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. has warned Philippine banks of the destabilizing
factors in the Philippines and the rest of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
In its November issue of Asian Fixed Income Monthly, the firm
said: "The turbulence in Southeast Asia generally and the
volatility in the peso continue to weaken the Philippine economy
and, in its wake, the operating environment for the banks."
</P>
<P>
The Philippine stock market has dropped more than 35 percent
since January, making it one of the worst performing stock markets
in the world this year, it said.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that political concerns regarding the May 1998
elections in the country were also an "unsettling force."
</P>
<P>
"This combination of factors is increasing the systemic
instability in the Philippine banking sectors," Merrill Lynch
said.
</P>
<P>
It said that these factors led to the significant slowing of
loan growth, deterioration in asset quality and greater premium of
defending balance sheet liquidity among Philippine banks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. firm estimated that the country's bank loans will
expand by only 20 percent to 25 percent this year from a high
growth of 52 percent in 1996 and 43 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that loan demand has declined significantly, after
being voracious up until the first quarter of 1997," it said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the slowdown in loan growth would persist until
next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
