<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Cancels Visit To Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
has decided to cancel a trip to Tehran, Iran, after being advised
to take a full 10-day rest because of fatigue, a senior official
announced here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
"The president's medical experts team has advised him to take a
rest," Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said, adding that
President Soeharto has thus decided to cancel his planned
participation in the upcoming summit of the Organization of
Islamic Conference (OIC) to be held in Tehran on December 9-11.
</P>
<P>
"The president has asked Foreign Minister Ali Alatas to
represent him at the OIC summit," Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that President Soeharto is in good health. "The
presidential doctors team is of the opinion that the health of the
president is in very good condition," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Moerdiono, President Soeharto's decision to take a
rest was made after a strenuous 12-day, three-continent trip that
included visits to Namibia, Canada and Saudi Arabia, where he
performed the minor haj (umroh) together with his children and
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto traveled a total of 28,500 kilometers on
this trip, Moerdiono said, adding: "This shows how strenuous the
president's trip has been."
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said the president would rest at his residence in
Jakarta and that he would continue to carry out state functions
from his Jalan Cendana residence. Only the most important
documents and correspondence would be forwarded to the president,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day rest will allow President Soeharto to attend the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) summit in Kuala
Lumpur, Malaysia, between December 14 and 16.
</P>
<P>
However, Moerdiono declined to confirm the president's
attendance at the ASEAN summit, saying "at the appropriate time, I
will give the information."
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who is widely expected to be reelected for a seventh
five-year term of office in a presidential election in March 1998,
underwent a thorough medical checkup in Germany in July last year,
and his doctors there gave him a clean bill of health.  
</P>
</TEXT>
