<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Call for Increase of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Many developing
countries have called for an increase of their representation in a
reformed Security Council of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Asian, African and Latin American countries made such appeal in
the debate on the reform of the Security Council of the 52nd
Session of the U.N. General Assembly this week.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahamd said the reform of
the Security Council should be based on the principles of
equitable geographical representation and sovereign equality of
states.
</P>
<P>
Representative of Egypt Nabil Elaraby, who spoke on behalf of
the Non-Aligned Movement, said the Movement is of the view that
the reform and expansion of the Council should be considered as
parts of a package that takes account of the sovereign equality of
states and the principle of equitable geographical distribution.
</P>
<P>
"The gross underrepresentation of the Non-Aligned states in the
Council should be corrected by its enlargement," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the reform of the Council should not be
limited to an increase in permanent seats for the developed
countries at the expense of the less developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's representative Issac E. Ayewah urged a correction of
non-African representation in the Council's permanent membership,
while pointing to the fact that Africa has the largest number of
U.N. member states which constitute almost one third of the U.N.
membership.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's representative Bruno Rodriguez Parrilla said the
Council's reform should guarantee representation for the
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Any reform and expansion should be carried out based on the
principles of transparency, sovereign equality of states and
equitable geographical distribution in accordance with the U.N.
Charter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's representative Volodymyr Yel'chenko said the Council
needs a more representative character, more support from member
states and a higher level of legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
He said Ukraine supports increased representation of the
developing countries in Africa, Asia and Latin America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The eastern European countries should also have an additional
non-permanent seat, he said.
</P>
<P>
Several countries rejected the so-called "quick fix" proposal
to admit several countries first into the Security Council without
wide consideration by member states.
</P>
<P>
"The enlargement (of the Council) should not have strict time
limits," Yel'chenko said.
</P>
<P>
Less than 60 countries spoke at the debate which stated on
Thursday. A draft resolution on the Council's reform has been put
before delegates for consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Surpasses 130-yen Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar reached its
third 5-year high against the yen this week and rose against other
major currencies Friday after a strong U.S. employment report.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 130.20 yen,
up from 129.39 late Thursday. It was the first time the U.S.
currency crossed the 130-yen level since May 1992.
</P>
<P>
The dollar surged in the morning session after the government
reported that a burst of job growth pushed the U.S. unemployment
rate to a 24-year low of 4.6 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
The bond market took an opposite response on the data, fearing
the Federal Reserve might feel the need to raise interest rates to
cool inflationary pressure. Investors drove bond prices down, but
that boosted the dollar by pushing interest rates higher.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was changing hands at 1.7830 marks, up from
1.7715. In addition, the U.S. currency climbed to a six-week high
against the British pound, which stood at 1.6573 U.S. dollars, up
from 1.6669 U.S. dollars on continued reaction to the Bank of
England's decision not to raise interest rates Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the currencies of South Korea, Malaysia, Singapore
and Indonesia all dropped against the dollar Friday.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday: 1.4400 Swiss francs, up from 1.4318; 5.9641 French
francs, up from 5.9260; 1,744 Italian lire, up from 1,736.70; and
1.4238 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4299.  
</P>
</TEXT>
