<HEADLINE> Survey: Americans Want Legal Intoxication Level Lowered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A survey released Friday
finds nearly seven in 10 Americans favor lowering the legal blood
alcohol content level below the current limits in most states,
according to a holiday season survey released Friday by Mothers
Against Drunk Driving.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 53 percent of respondents ranked drunken drivers
as the nation's No. 1 highway safety problem, followed by people
who drive too fast, the survey by Mothers Against Drunk Driving
(MADD) said.
</P>
<P>
The survey, sponsored by the Allstate Insurance Co., is part of
a push for legislation introduced in Congress, that would require
states to lower their legal blood alcohol content levels to 0.08
percent or risk losing some of their federal highway aid. The
measure has not advanced out of House and Senate committees.
</P>
<P>
"We are... calling on our government here in the nation's
capital and in every state capital to take swift and decisive
action to combat this major public health and safety problem,"
Katherine Prescott, MADD national president, said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four states and the District of Columbia enforce 0.1
percent blood alcohol levels, while 15 states already have the
lower 0.08 percent limit. According to the survey, 69 percent of
respondents would like to see the level lowered to 0.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 31 percent of people admit they have driven
after drinking too much.
</P>
<P>
But Rick Berman, general counsel of the American Beverage
Institute, which represents thousands of restaurants, said
"Clearly, drunk driving, though it is a problem, is not one of the
biggest problems on the national roadways."
</P>
<P>
Berman said speeding and overly aggressive driving were more
serious.
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey of 1,000 Americans was conducted by the
Market Facts research firm November 3-5. The margin of error
is approximately plus or minus 3 percentage points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: No Date Set for New Force out of Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States and its
allies have not decided whether to fix a deadline for a new
peace-keeping force in Bosnia to get out of the region, U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen said today.
</P>
<P>
The subject was controversial in the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and in the U.S. Congress, which must approve
funding for any U.S. participation in further peacekeeping in
Bosnia, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary made the remarks on way back from his
Europe tour, according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
"There is great division on this subject matter still on the
Hill (Capitol Hill). There was a division among the European
members" of NATO, Cohen said of discussions at an alliance defense
ministers meeting in Brussels this week.
</P>
<P>
"There was no consensus at the meeting about whether there
should be a specific end date or end state," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There was, I think, a general feeling, however, that specific
time lines and dates were generally not advisable. We have said
that ourselves."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies will pull out all their 30,000 troops
of the so-called Stabilization Force (SFOR) based in Bosnia and
are considering a smaller follow-on force to continue the
peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said in Paris
that any follow-on force to SFOR should be kept under review for
possible pull-out rather than be given a fixed date to get out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
