<HEADLINE> Earthquake-Lead Tsunami Warning for Alaska Canceled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Tsunami Warning Center
in Alaska canceled a tsunami warning and watch for parts of Alaska
and British Columbia issued after a strong earthquake in
Kamchatka, Russia's Far East earlier today.
</P>
<P>
The quake occurred at 7:27 a m. (1127 GMT) and was registered
7.7 on the Richter scale. The center said it was centered 130
kilometers off the coast of the Kamchatka Peninsula in
northeastern Russia that just into the Bering and Okhotsk seas.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the quake, the Alaska tsunami center issued the
warning for the coastal area of the U.S. state, from Attu to Dutch
Harbor, and a watch covering the northern tip of Vancouver Island,
British Columbia, to Dutch Harbor.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here quoted Kamchatka officials as saying that
there was no tsunami and no damages reported. 
</P>
