<HEADLINE> Official: China Has Positive Results in Bilaterals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Positive results have been
achieved in China's bilateral market access negotiations with
members of the World Trade Organization (WTO), a senior Chinese
trade official said here today.
</P>
<P>
China has conducted bilateral market access negotiations with
35 WTO members so far, and the bilateral negotiations with more
than 20 members have approached the final stage, said Long Yongtu,
China's vice minister of foreign trade and chief trade
representative.
</P>
<P>
China has signed bilateral agreements with the Czech Republic,
Hungary, Japan, Korea, Pakistan, New Zealand, and Slovakia, Long
said at the one-day meeting of the Working Party on China's
accession here today. Two or three more countries will signed
bilateral agreements with China in the following weeks.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government highly appreciates the positive and
practical spirit demonstrated by these countries in the bilateral
negotiations, and is grateful for their understanding and support
to China's WTO accession," Long said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that with political will and a practical and
flexible attitude, bilateral negotiations with even more members
will be concluded in the near future," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
