<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long Urges WTO Members to Accelerate China's Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- China's chief trade
representative Long Yongtu today urged members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) to speed up negotiations over China's accession
to the organization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a one-day meeting of the WTO Working Party on China
here today, Long reminded the members to bear in mind the ultimate
objective of China's 11-year-long negotiation as the year 1997
comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the objective of China's WTO accession, on the
one hand, is to commit China to the WTO rules," Long said. "On the
other hand, it is to gradually bring China's opening up of its
market in line with the level of the majority of the WTO members."
</P>
<P>
"The earlier China accedes to the WTO, the earlier China will
implement its commitment to the WTO rules," he pointed out. "To
prolong the negotiation process is, in fact, to delay China's
implementation of its obligation in the WTO."
</P>
<P>
Long hoped that China would join the WTO no later than the end
of 1999. "According to the built-in WTO agenda, the next round of
negotiations on trade in services will begin on January 1, 2000,"
he explained. "We hope that China could participate in this round
of negotiation as a full member of the WTO." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., EU Leaders Discuss Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
met with leaders of the European Union (EU) today on a broad range
of issues, including differences between the U.S. and EU on
environment protection and trade.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met in the Oval Office with European Commission
President Jacques Santer, Luxembourg Prime Minister Jean-Claude
Juncker, whose country currently holds the EU presidency, and EU
Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan.
</P>
<P>
"Today's summit is giving us an opportunity to review progress
in the transatlantic relationship at the conclusion of
Luxembourg's presidency of the EU," State Department spokesman
James Foley.
</P>
<P>
"Our leaders have been renewing our commitment to the U.S-EU
new transatlantic agenda and continuing their discussions on a
wide range of critical issues," Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
As part of the one-day summit, which is held biannually, the EU
and the U.S. agreed to make it easier to exchange information in
science and technology research.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed a first-ever U.S.-EU Science and
Technology Agreement and also agreed to a pathfinding joint
statement on electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
Although officials of both sides stressed the spirit of
cooperation in the talks, there were still some serious
disagreements.
</P>
<P>
Following the end of the Cold War, splits between EU and the
U.S. have been increasing as their common enemy, the Soviet Union,
does no longer exist.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have differences in areas ranging from trade to
security, such as Bosnia issues and EU grievances over U.S. laws
that threaten to penalize companies that invest in Cuba, Iran or
Libya.
</P>
<P>
The summit will also focus on their differences on limiting
greenhouse gas emissions that makes the planet warmer.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials stressed that the talks were not a negotiating
session to resolve an impasse between Europe and Washington over
limiting greenhouse gas emissions, but Clinton told reporters he
was guardedly optimistic a compromise could be reached at talks
under way in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
"We want this to be the beginning of a process which eventually
will have everyone in the world involved in dealing with this
issue," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the chances that we can get an agreement are
reasonably good if everybody there really wants an agreement and
we want to see countries bound to targets which will lead us to
reduce greenhouse gas emissions," Clinton said. "That's the real
test."
</P>
<P>
More than 160 countries are meeting in Kyoto until Dec. 10 to
discuss ways to curb a series of gases that scientists say
threaten to cause global climate changes.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposes reducing emissions to the levels that existed
in 1990 within the next 10 to 15 years while EU champions a 15
percent reduction below 1990 levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Chances Exist to Reach Agreement at Kyoto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today here that there were opportunities to reach a global
agreement in reducing greenhouse gases at a world climate meeting
in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the chances that we can get an agreement are
reasonably good if everybody there really wants an agreement,"
Clinton told reporters before meeting European Union leaders.
</P>
<P>
"We're working in Kyoto to try to get an agreement and we'll
see if we can. We hope we can," Clinton said. "We want to see
countries bound to targets which will lead us to reduce greenhouse
gas emissions. That's the real test."
</P>
<P>
The EU has pledged a 15 percent reduction on 1990 emissions of
three greenhouse gases by 2010 while the U.S. wants to stabilize
emissions at 1990 levels by 2008-2012.
</P>
<P>
The United States said it was difficult to promise more than
that concerning economic costs. U.S. Vice President Al Gore said
earlier this week Washington was willing to walk away from any
pact that it does not believe is workable.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said it was not impossible to make compromises on
the issue "if everybody wants an agreement."
</P>
<P>
"Our position is that it's a global issue. We want to get
global involvement and we want this to be the beginning of a
process which eventually will have everybody in the world involved
in dealing with this issue."
</P>
<P>
At the conference, developing nations asked the United States
and other industrial nations to take tougher actions to lead the
world in the fight against greenhouse gases emission as they are
the major gases producers.
</P>
<P>
Scientists fear that greenhouse gases will cause climate change
in the form of more fierce, frequent storms, regional flooding,
droughts and melting of polar ice caps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971206.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Crisis Slows Down World Economic Growth: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Facing with the wide-spread
financial crisis in Asia, the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
said today the chaos may soon be tamed but has already cut nearly
one percentage point off world economic growth next year.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing held at its headquarters here, IMF Deputy
Managing Director Stanley Fischer and other officials made the
latest prediction, a day after the IMF's 24-member executive board
gave its green light to a 21 billion U.S. dollar loan program for
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The IMF loans will be part of a international package for South
Korea that is expected to top 60 billion dollars, making it the
largest bailout in IMF history, surpassing the 50 billion dollar
program for Mexico in earlier 1995.
</P>
<P>
In Summer this year, Thailand received approval for a 17.2
billion dollar bailout package and again in October, Indonesia was
provided with a 40 billion dollar bailout package soon after they
were rocked by plunging currencies, stock market declines and
spreading bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
Fischer pointed out that it was essential for these Asian
nations to follow the stiff reform programs they agreed to in
return for the IMF bailout assistance so that they can stabilize
the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident these programs will succeed if fully
implemented," he said. "We are confident that doing so is the best
way to restore growth of the miracle economies of Asia."
</P>
<P>
However, Fischer also noted the fallout from the turmoil, which
resulted in the biggest one-day point loss in Wall Street history,
has already taken a toll on the world economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF has revised its estimate for economic growth to
3.5 percent for 1998, down from its 4.3 percent forecast just last
September.
</P>
<P>
Some economists have predicted that growth in the United States
is likely to be reduced by one-half percentage point next year,
reflecting slower growth in U.S. exports to the troubled Asian
economies and higher imports from those countries because their
weaker currencies will make their products cheaper in the U.S.
market.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said that at one point South Korea was perhaps only 10
days away from "financial catastrophe" because of the dramatic
drain on the country's reserves.
</P>
<P>
But Fischer said in recent days there have been a number of
encouraging signs that the worst of the South Korean crisis has
passed. The currency and the stock market have both risen in
recent days and the huge drawdown on reserves has slowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
