<HEADLINE> S. African Economic Growth Slows Down in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The South African Reserve
Bank has cut its economic growth predictions for 1997 as clearer
evidence has shown that the economy is not producing at full
capacity, the South African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its December quarterly bulletin that the
economy should grow at between 1.5 and two percent in the 1997
calendar year.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals had expected gross domestic
product (GDP) to grow by around 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The economy expanded three percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Although a technical analysis could not provide conclusive
evidence of a downward phase of the business cycle, the economy
was definitely not producing at full capacity," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said output growth clearly did not match the economy's
growth potential in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The announcement followed a similar move by Finance Minister
Trevor Manuel earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said on Tuesday at the launch of the government's
three-year budget plan that he forecast GDP growth at two percent
for the 1997/98 financial year, lower than an initial estimate of
2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The South African Chamber of Business today also cut its
prediction to 1.8 percent for 1997, against a previous downgrade
to two percent just two months ago.
</P>
<P>
It also cut its growth forecast for 1998 from three to 2.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Central Statistical Service figures showed that growth slumped
to only 0.3 percent in the third quarter of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
