<HEADLINE> Clinton Says New Ideas Needed for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
said on Friday the Middle East peace process should be pushed
forward with "some new ideas".
</P>
<P>
Speaking with reporters at the White House, Clinton said
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had brought these ideas to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat when she met Netanyahu in Paris on Friday and
Arafat in Geneva on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We have some new ideas at least about the process, about
where to go from here, at least different approaches and we hope
that it will move the ball forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the president did not elaborate what new Ideas they were.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Netanyahu and Arafat, Clinton said: "I think
they both understand that this is a time when something needs to
be done to show concrete progress. I'm encouraged ... we'll just
have to see what happens."
</P>
<P>
Albright held about three-hour talks with Netanyahu in Paris
earlier on Friday and reports said there was no breakthrough in
reviving the stalemated peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinians, which suspended in March as a result of Israel's
decision to build Jewish housing units in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the Paris talks, Albright said
time was pressing for both Israelis and Palestinians to take
hard decisions to break the nine-month deadlock in their
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides have to put their shoulders to the wheel and
understand that time is of the essence," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright was pressing the Israeli leader to set a timetable
for the redeployment of the Israeli troops on the West Bank, but
Netanyahu rebuffed her pressure, saying: "We've had our problems."


nnnn
